{"title_page": "Arturo Ithurralde", "text_new": "'''Arturo Andr\u00e9s Ithurralde''' (March 6, 1934 \u2013 June 3, 2017) was [[Argentina|Argentine]] [[football (soccer)|football referee]]. He was known for having refereed one match in the [[1982 FIFA World Cup]] in [[Spain]]. He also refereed four matches at [[1975 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1975]] and [[1983 Copa Am\u00e9rica]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/2030391-murio-arturo-ithurralde-recordado-arbitro-de-los-anos-70|title=Muri\u00f3 Arturo Ithurralde, recordado \u00e1rbitro de los a\u00f1os '70|website=lanacion.com.ar|language=es|date=4 June 2017|accessdate=5 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929111210/http://www.weltfussball.de/schiedsrichter_profil.php?id=26586 |title=Profile at WeltFussball.de}} {{in lang|de}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{WorldReferee.com}}\n* {{WorldFootball.net referee}}\n* {{Soccerway referee|arturo-andres-ithurralde/108049}}\n\n{{1982 FIFA World Cup referees}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ithurralde}}\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:Argentine people of Basque descent]]\n[[Category:Argentine football referees]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup referees]]\n[[Category:1982 FIFA World Cup referees]]\n[[Category:Copa Am\u00e9rica referees]]\n\n\n{{Argentina-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Arturo Andr\u00e9s Ithurralde''' (March 6, 1934 \u2013 June 3, 2017) was [[Argentina|Argentine]] [[football (soccer)|football referee]]. He was known for having refereed one match in the [[1982 FIFA World Cup]] in [[Spain]]. He also refereed four matches at [[1975 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1975]] and [[1983 Copa Am\u00e9rica]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/2030391-murio-arturo-ithurralde-recordado-arbitro-de-los-anos-70|title=Muri\u00f3 Arturo Ithurralde, recordado \u00e1rbitro de los a\u00f1os '70|website=lanacion.com.ar|accessdate=5 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070929111210/http://www.weltfussball.de/schiedsrichter_profil.php?id=26586 Profile]\n{{1982 FIFA World Cup referees}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ithurralde}}\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:Argentine people of Basque descent]]\n[[Category:Argentine football referees]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup referees]]\n[[Category:1982 FIFA World Cup referees]]\n[[Category:Copa Am\u00e9rica referees]]\n\n{{Argentina-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "add referee link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arturo_Ithurralde"}
{"title_page": "Weekend Today (Australian TV program)", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Weekend Today\n| image                    = \n| caption                  = \n| show_name_2              = \n| genre                    = [[Breakfast television|Breakfast news program]]\n| creator                  = \n| based_on                 = \n| developer                = \n| writer                   = \n| director                 = \n| creative_director        = \n| presenter                = [[Richard Wilkins (TV presenter)|Richard Wilkins]]<br> [[Rebecca Maddern]]\n| judges                   = \n| voices                   = \n| narrated                 = \n| theme_music_composer     = \n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = \n| country                  = [[Australia]]\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 10\n| num_episodes             = 526 (as of 27 April 2014)\n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = Kendall Bora\n| producer                 = \n| location                 = [[Willoughby, New South Wales]]\n| cinematography           = \n| editor                   = \n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = 180 minutes\n| company                  = \n| distributor              = \n| network                  = [[Nine Network]]\n| picture_format           = [[576i]] ([[SDTV]])<br />[[1080i]] ([[high-definition television|HDTV]])\n| audio_format             = Stereo\n| first_aired              = 1 February 2009\n| last_aired               = present\n| preceded_by              = ''[[Sunday (Australian TV program)|Sunday]]''<br />''[[Nine News#Sunday Morning News|Sunday Morning News]]''\n| related                  = ''[[Today (Australian TV program)|Today]]''<br/>''[[Today Extra]]''\n| website                  = https://www.9now.com.au/today\n| production_website       = \n| image_alt                = \n| channel                  = Channel 9\n| first_run                = \n| released                 = \n}}\n\n'''''Weekend Today''''' is an Australian breakfast television program, currently hosted by [[Richard Wilkins (TV presenter)|Richard Wilkins]] and [[Rebecca Maddern]].\nThe program has been broadcast live by the [[Nine Network]] since 2009 and airs after children's programming and runs from 7am to 10am on weekends.\n\n== History ==\nIn January 2009, [[David Gyngell]], chief executive of the Nine Network and John Westacott, former head of news and current affairs announced that ''Today'' would begin broadcasting on Sunday mornings. The program entitled, ''Today on Sunday'', competes in the same timeslot as the [[Seven Network]]'s ''[[Weekend Sunrise]]'', which dominates Sunday morning television nationally, except on the east coast. The show launched on 1 February 2009 and the original team consisted of [[Cameron Williams]] and [[Leila McKinnon]] with the news presented by [[Amber Sherlock]] and the sport was presented by Tim Gilbert on Saturday and [[Michael Slater]] on Sunday.<ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Today Launching Sunday Edition|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2009/01/today-launching-sunday-edition.html|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=4 January 2009|accessdate=4 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Weekend Sunrise wakes up to Today\u2019s alarm|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2009/01/weekend-sunrise-wakes-up-to-todays-alarm.html|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=28 January 2009|accessdate=28 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 May 2009, after the launch of ''Today on Sunday'', the Nine Network announced through a surprise edition that ''Today on Saturday'' would return. The program incorporates the same presenting team as the Sunday edition, being the first Australian breakfast news program to broadcast seven days a week. Due to the launch of the Saturday version of the program, the Nine Network renamed the programs as ''Today: Weekend Edition''. David Gyngell said the launch of the Weekend editions were a part of the Nine Network's plans to strengthen its news and current affairs department and return viewers to its once leading news service.<ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Today's Surprise Saturday|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2009/05/todays-surprise-saturday.html|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=3 May 2009|accessdate=3 May 2009}}</ref> In July 2009, ''Today: Weekend Edition'' was rebranded as ''Weekend Today''.\n\nIn September 2012, ''Weekend Today'' was extended to 3 hours on Saturday mornings.\n\nIn September 2014, [[Deborah Knight]] permanently replaced Leila McKinnon as co-host of the show; following McKinnon's move to the News Department.\n\nIn February 2016, Cameron Williams announced his resignation from the Nine Network.<ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Cameron Williams Exits Nine|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2016/02/cameron-williams-exits-nine.html|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=10 February 2016|accessdate=10 February 2016}}</ref> Peter Stefanovic took over as co-host.<ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Peter Stefanovic for Weekend Today|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2016/02/peter-stefanovic-tipped-for-weekend-today.html|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=12 February 2016|accessdate=12 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, Peter Stefanovic announced that he would be moving to [[60 Minutes (Australian TV program)|''60 Minutes'']] in 2017 as a reporter.<ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Peter Stefanovic to Join 60 Minutes|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2016/11/peter-stefanovic-to-join-60-minutes.html|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=19 November 2016|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> Tom Steinfort has been announced as Stefanovic's replacement.<ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Nine News Promotes Team With New Appointments|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2016/12/nine-news-promotes-team-with-new-appointments.html|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=8 December 2016|accessdate=8 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Knight was appointed as host of [[Nine News|''Nine News Sydney'']] on Friday and Saturday nights. She replaced [[Georgie Gardner]] who replaced [[Lisa Wilkinson]] on [[Today (Australian TV program)|''Today'']]. It was later announced that [[60 Minutes (Australian TV program)|''60 Minutes'']] reporter Allison Langdon would replace Knight on ''Weekend Today''.<ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Deb Knight Moves To Primetime|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2017/12/deb-knight-moves-to-primetime.html|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=13 December 2017|accessdate=13 December 2017}}</ref> Peter Stefanovic also returned as host replacing Tom Steinfort who will become a reporter on ''60 Minutes''.<ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Tom Steinfort Joins 60 Minutes|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2018/01/tom-steinfort-joins-60-minutes.html|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=8 January 2018|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Allison Langdon & Peter Stefanovic For Weekend Today|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2018/01/allison-langdon-peter-stefanovic-for-weekend-today.html|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=10 January 2018|accessdate=10 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, it was announced that Peter Stefanovic had parted ways with the Nine Network to pursue other opportunities.<ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Peter Stefanovic Quits Nine|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2018/12/peter-stefanovic-quits-nine.html|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=18 December 2018|accessdate=18 December 2018}}</ref> In January 2019, ''[[Today Extra]]'' host [[David Campbell (singer)|David Campbell]] was appointed as Stefanvoic\u2019s replacement. Clint Stanaway also joined the team as a sport presenter and Tim Davies as weather presenter.<ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Deb Knight, Tom Steinfort Join Georgie On Today|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2019/01/deb-knight-tom-steinfort-join-georgie-on-today.html|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=5 January 2019|accessdate=5 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, it was announced that Langdon will leave the program to co-host ''[[Today (Australian TV program)|Today]]'' from January 2020. In December 2019, it was announced that ''[[Today Extra]]'' host [[Richard Wilkins (TV presenter)|Richard Wilkins]] will replace Campbell, co-hosting alongside [[Rebecca Maddern]]. Jayne Azzopardi will continue to present news and Lauren Phillips will present weather.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2019/12/confirmed-news-sport-weather-faces-for-today-show.html|title=Confirmed News, Sport & Weather Faces for Today Show|work=[[TV Tonight]]|date=18 December 2019|accessdate=18 December 2019|first=David|last=Knox}}</ref>\n\n== Hosts ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Presenter\n!Role\n!Tenure\n|-\n|[[Richard Wilkins (TV presenter)|Richard Wilkins]]\n|Co-host\n|2020\u2013present\n|-\n|[[Rebecca Maddern]]\n|Co-host\n|2020\u2013present\n|-\n|Jayne Azzopardi<sup>1</sup> \n|News & Sport\n|2016\u2013present\n|-\n|Lauren Phillips\n|Weather\n|2020\u2013present\n|}\n<sup>1</sup> Jayne Azzopardi is currently on maternity leave with Lara Vella presenting news and sport in her absence.\n\n=== Anchors  ===\nThe hosts ''Weekend Today'' have included:\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Hosts of Weekend Today !! Tenure \n|-\n|[[Cameron Williams]] and [[Leila McKinnon]]  || 2009 \u2013 2014 \n|-\n|[[Cameron Williams]] and [[Deborah Knight]]  || 2014 \u2013 2016 \n|-\n|[[Peter Stefanovic]] and [[Deborah Knight]]|| 2016 \n|-\n| Tom Steinfort and [[Deborah Knight]]  || 2017 \n|-\n|[[Peter Stefanovic]] and [[Allison Langdon]]  || 2018 \n|-\n|[[David Campbell (singer)|David Campbell]] and [[Allison Langdon]]  || 2019\n|-\n|[[Richard Wilkins (TV presenter)|Richard Wilkins]] and [[Rebecca Maddern]]  || 2020 \u2013 present\n|}\n\n=== Substitute hosts ===\nFill-in hosts for ''Weekend Today'' include Jayne Azzopardi, Tom Steinfort, Brett McLeod and Belinda Russell.\n\nSubstitute presenters in recent years have included [[Amelia Adams]], [[Wendy Kingston]], [[David Campbell (Australian musician)|David Campbell]], Dougal Beatty, [[Tim Gilbert (journalist)|Tim Gilbert]], [[Sylvia Jeffreys]], [[Alicia Loxley]], Davina Smith, Belinda Russell, [[Ben Fordham]], [[Ken Sutcliffe]], [[Natalia Cooper]], [[Tony Jones (sports journalist)|Tony Jones]], Brenton Ragless, [[Natalie Gruzlewski]], [[Sarah Harris (journalist)|Sarah Harris]], [[Shelley Craft]], Clint Stanaway, [[Ross Greenwood (journalist)|Ross Greenwood]], Chris Urquhart and [[Jonathan Uptin]].\n\n=== News ===\nNews presenters have included:\n\n* [[Amber Sherlock]] (2009 \u2013 2010)\n* [[Alicia Loxley|Alicia Gorey]] (2010 \u2013 2011)\n* [[Deborah Knight]] (December 2011 \u2013 May 2014)\n* [[Sylvia Jeffreys]] (May 2014 \u2013 June 2014)\n* [[Wendy Kingston]] (July 2014 \u2013 November 2015)\n* Jayne Azzopardi (2016 \u2013 present)\n\nLara Vella, Mark Burrows, Belinda Russell, Sarah Stewart and Vanessa O'Hanlon are fill-in news presenters.\n\n=== Sport ===\nSport presenters have included:\n* [[Michael Slater]] (Sunday: 2009 \u2013 2010)\n* [[Tim Gilbert (journalist)|Tim Gilbert]] (Saturday: 2009 \u2013 2010)\n* [[Tim Gilbert (journalist)|Tim Gilbert]] (2010\u2013September 2014)\n* [[Nathan Brown (Australian footballer born 1978)|Nathan Brown]] (September 2014 \u2013 December 2014)\n* [[Cameron Williams]] (2015 \u2013 2016)\n* Tom Steinfort (2016 \u2013 2017)\n* Peter Stefanovic (2016; 2018)\n* Clint Stanaway (2019)\n*Jayne Azzopardi (2020 \u2013 present)\n\n=== Weather ===\nIn December 2009, Felicity Whelan began presenting the weather on ''Weekend Today'' after she was chosen through the weekend weather competition, Whelan also filled in for [[Steven Jacobs (television presenter)|Steven Jacobs]] on ''Today''.\nHowever, in April 2010, main fill-in weather presenter, [[Emma Freedman]] replaced Whelan who joined [[Network Ten]]. Due to budget cuts at the Nine Network, Freedman was made redundant in late 2014. In 2015, [[Natalia Cooper]] was appointed as weather presenter. In December 2016, Steve Jacobs announced that he would be leaving ''Today'' to join ''Weekend Today'' as weather presenter. In March 2019, it was announced that ''[[Nine News]]'' reporter Tim Davies would join the team as weather presenter. In December 2019, Lauren Phillips was announced as ''Weekend Today'' weather presenter replacing Tim Davies who was promoted to ''[[Today (Australian TV program)|Today]]'' weather presenter.\n\nWeather presenters have included:\n* Felicity Whelan (2009 \u2013 2010)\n* [[Emma Freedman]] (2010 \u2013 2014)\n* [[Natalia Cooper]] (2015 \u2013 2016)\n* [[Steven Jacobs (television presenter)|Steve Jacobs]] (2017 \u2013 2018)\n* Tim Davies (2019)\n* Lauren Phillips (2019 \u2013 present)\n\n=== Entertainment ===\nIn February 2009, [[Michele Mahone]] joined ''Weekend Today'' as Hollywood Gossip reporter where she reported on the latest entertainment news. She remained with the show until September 2013 due to the show going in 'another direction'. That other direction was Susanne Messara who presented the latest entertainment news from the couch. This idea failed and media personality Giselle Ugarte was appointed entertainment presenter situated again in Hollywood. In 2015, Daily Telegraph columnist Elle Halliwell was appointed entertainment presenter replacing Ugarte. Halliwell along with the entertainment segments were removed shortly after.\n\nEntertainment presenters have included:\n* [[Michele Mahone]] (2009 \u2013 2013)\n* Susanne Messara (2013 \u2013 2014)\n* Gisele Ugarte (2014)\n* Elle Halliwell (2015)\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Australian television series]]\n* [[List of programs broadcast by Nine Network]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://www.9now.com.au/today}}\n\n{{TodayPresenters}}\n{{News & Current Affairs in Australia}}\n{{Nine Network programming}}\n{{AustralianWeekendBreakfastShows}}\n\n[[Category:Nine News|*]]\n[[Category:2009 Australian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2000s Australian television series]]\n[[Category:2010s Australian television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Sydney]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Weekend Today\n| image                    = \n| caption                  = \n| show_name_2              = \n| genre                    = [[Breakfast television|Breakfast news program]]\n| creator                  = \n| based_on                 = \n| developer                = \n| writer                   = \n| director                 = \n| creative_director        = \n| presenter                = [[Richard Wilkins (TV presenter)|Richard Wilkins]]<br> [[Rebecca Maddern]]\n| judges                   = \n| voices                   = \n| narrated                 = \n| theme_music_composer     = \n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = \n| country                  = [[Australia]]\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 10\n| num_episodes             = 526 (as of 27 April 2014)\n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = Kendall Bora\n| producer                 = \n| location                 = [[Willoughby, New South Wales]]\n| cinematography           = \n| editor                   = \n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = 180 minutes\n| company                  = \n| distributor              = \n| network                  = [[Nine Network]]\n| picture_format           = [[576i]] ([[SDTV]])<br />[[1080i]] ([[high-definition television|HDTV]])\n| audio_format             = Stereo\n| first_aired              = 1 February 2009\n| last_aired               = present\n| preceded_by              = ''[[Sunday (Australian TV program)|Sunday]]''<br />''[[Nine News#Sunday Morning News|Sunday Morning News]]''\n| related                  = ''[[Today (Australian TV program)|Today]]''<br/>''[[Today Extra]]''\n| website                  = https://www.9now.com.au/today\n| production_website       = \n| image_alt                = \n| channel                  = Channel 9\n| first_run                = \n| released                 = \n}}\n\n'''''Weekend Today''''' is an Australian breakfast television program, currently hosted by [[Richard Wilkins (TV presenter)|Richard Wilkins]] and [[Rebecca Maddern]].\nThe program has been broadcast live by the [[Nine Network]] since 2009 and airs after children's programming and runs from 7am to 10am on weekends.\n\n== History ==\nIn January 2009, [[David Gyngell]], chief executive of the Nine Network and John Westacott, former head of news and current affairs announced that ''Today'' would begin broadcasting on Sunday mornings. The program entitled, ''Today on Sunday'', competes in the same timeslot as the [[Seven Network]]'s ''[[Weekend Sunrise]]'', which dominates Sunday morning television nationally, except on the east coast. The show launched on 1 February 2009 and the original team consisted of [[Cameron Williams]] and [[Leila McKinnon]] with the news presented by [[Amber Sherlock]] and the sport was presented by Tim Gilbert on Saturday and [[Michael Slater]] on Sunday.<ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Today Launching Sunday Edition|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2009/01/today-launching-sunday-edition.html|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=4 January 2009|accessdate=4 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Weekend Sunrise wakes up to Today\u2019s alarm|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2009/01/weekend-sunrise-wakes-up-to-todays-alarm.html|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=28 January 2009|accessdate=28 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 May 2009, after the launch of ''Today on Sunday'', the Nine Network announced through a surprise edition that ''Today on Saturday'' would return. The program incorporates the same presenting team as the Sunday edition, being the first Australian breakfast news program to broadcast seven days a week. Due to the launch of the Saturday version of the program, the Nine Network renamed the programs as ''Today: Weekend Edition''. David Gyngell said the launch of the Weekend editions were a part of the Nine Network's plans to strengthen its news and current affairs department and return viewers to its once leading news service.<ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Today's Surprise Saturday|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2009/05/todays-surprise-saturday.html|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=3 May 2009|accessdate=3 May 2009}}</ref> In July 2009, ''Today: Weekend Edition'' was rebranded as ''Weekend Today''.\n\nIn September 2012, ''Weekend Today'' was extended to 3 hours on Saturday mornings.\n\nIn September 2014, [[Deborah Knight]] permanently replaced Leila McKinnon as co-host of the show; following McKinnon's move to the News Department.\n\nIn February 2016, Cameron Williams announced his resignation from the Nine Network.<ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Cameron Williams Exits Nine|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2016/02/cameron-williams-exits-nine.html|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=10 February 2016|accessdate=10 February 2016}}</ref> Peter Stefanovic took over as co-host.<ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Peter Stefanovic for Weekend Today|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2016/02/peter-stefanovic-tipped-for-weekend-today.html|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=12 February 2016|accessdate=12 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, Peter Stefanovic announced that he would be moving to [[60 Minutes (Australian TV program)|''60 Minutes'']] in 2017 as a reporter.<ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Peter Stefanovic to Join 60 Minutes|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2016/11/peter-stefanovic-to-join-60-minutes.html|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=19 November 2016|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> Tom Steinfort has been announced as Stefanovic's replacement.<ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Nine News Promotes Team With New Appointments|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2016/12/nine-news-promotes-team-with-new-appointments.html|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=8 December 2016|accessdate=8 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Knight was appointed as host of [[Nine News|''Nine News Sydney'']] on Friday and Saturday nights. She replaced [[Georgie Gardner]] who replaced [[Lisa Wilkinson]] on [[Today (Australian TV program)|''Today'']]. It was later announced that [[60 Minutes (Australian TV program)|''60 Minutes'']] reporter Allison Langdon would replace Knight on ''Weekend Today''.<ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Deb Knight Moves To Primetime|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2017/12/deb-knight-moves-to-primetime.html|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=13 December 2017|accessdate=13 December 2017}}</ref> Peter Stefanovic also returned as host replacing Tom Steinfort who will become a reporter on ''60 Minutes''.<ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Tom Steinfort Joins 60 Minutes|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2018/01/tom-steinfort-joins-60-minutes.html|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=8 January 2018|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Allison Langdon & Peter Stefanovic For Weekend Today|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2018/01/allison-langdon-peter-stefanovic-for-weekend-today.html|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=10 January 2018|accessdate=10 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, it was announced that Peter Stefanovic had parted ways with the Nine Network to pursue other opportunities.<ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Peter Stefanovic Quits Nine|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2018/12/peter-stefanovic-quits-nine.html|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=18 December 2018|accessdate=18 December 2018}}</ref> In January 2019, ''[[Today Extra]]'' host [[David Campbell (singer)|David Campbell]] was appointed as Stefanvoic\u2019s replacement. Clint Stanaway also joined the team as a sport presenter and Tim Davies as weather presenter.<ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Deb Knight, Tom Steinfort Join Georgie On Today|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2019/01/deb-knight-tom-steinfort-join-georgie-on-today.html|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=5 January 2019|accessdate=5 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, it was announced that Langdon will leave the program to co-host ''[[Today (Australian TV program)|Today]]'' from January 2020. In December 2019, it was announced that ''[[Today Extra]]'' host [[Richard Wilkins (TV presenter)|Richard Wilkins]] will replace Campbell, co-hosting alongside [[Rebecca Maddern]]. Jayne Azzopardi will continue to present news and Lauren Phillips will present weather.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2019/12/confirmed-news-sport-weather-faces-for-today-show.html|title=Confirmed News, Sport & Weather Faces for Today Show|work=[[TV Tonight]]|date=18 December 2019|accessdate=18 December 2019|first=David|last=Knox}}</ref>\n\n== Hosts ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Presenter\n!Role\n!Tenure\n|-\n|[[Richard Wilkins (TV presenter)|Richard Wilkins]]\n|Co-host\n|2020\u2013present\n|-\n|[[Rebecca Maddern]]\n|Co-host\n|2020\u2013present\n|-\n|Jayne Azzopardi<sup>1</sup> \n|News & Sport\n|2020\u2013present\n|-\n|Lauren Phillips\n|Weather\n|2020\u2013present\n|}\n<sup>1</sup> Jayne Azzopardi is currently on maternity leave with Lara Vella presenting news and sport in her absence.\n\n=== Anchors  ===\nThe hosts ''Weekend Today'' have included:\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Hosts of Weekend Today !! Tenure \n|-\n|[[Cameron Williams]] and [[Leila McKinnon]]  || 2009 \u2013 2014 \n|-\n|[[Cameron Williams]] and [[Deborah Knight]]  || 2014 \u2013 2016 \n|-\n|[[Peter Stefanovic]] and [[Deborah Knight]]|| 2016 \n|-\n| Tom Steinfort and [[Deborah Knight]]  || 2017 \n|-\n|[[Peter Stefanovic]] and [[Allison Langdon]]  || 2018 \n|-\n|[[David Campbell (singer)|David Campbell]] and [[Allison Langdon]]  || 2019\n|-\n|[[Richard Wilkins (TV presenter)|Richard Wilkins]] and [[Rebecca Maddern]]  || 2020 \u2013 present\n|}\n\n=== Substitute hosts ===\nFill-in hosts for ''Weekend Today'' include Jayne Azzopardi, Tom Steinfort, Brett McLeod and Belinda Russell.\n\nSubstitute presenters in recent years have included [[Amelia Adams]], [[Wendy Kingston]], [[David Campbell (Australian musician)|David Campbell]], Dougal Beatty, [[Tim Gilbert (journalist)|Tim Gilbert]], [[Sylvia Jeffreys]], [[Alicia Loxley]], Davina Smith, Belinda Russell, [[Ben Fordham]], [[Ken Sutcliffe]], [[Natalia Cooper]], [[Tony Jones (sports journalist)|Tony Jones]], Brenton Ragless, [[Natalie Gruzlewski]], [[Sarah Harris (journalist)|Sarah Harris]], [[Shelley Craft]], Clint Stanaway, [[Ross Greenwood (journalist)|Ross Greenwood]], Chris Urquhart and [[Jonathan Uptin]].\n\n=== News ===\nNews presenters have included:\n\n* [[Amber Sherlock]] (2009 \u2013 2010)\n* [[Alicia Loxley|Alicia Gorey]] (2010 \u2013 2011)\n* [[Deborah Knight]] (December 2011 \u2013 May 2014)\n* [[Sylvia Jeffreys]] (May 2014 \u2013 June 2014)\n* [[Wendy Kingston]] (July 2014 \u2013 November 2015)\n* Jayne Azzopardi (2016 \u2013 present)\n\nLara Vella, Mark Burrows, Belinda Russell, Sarah Stewart and Vanessa O'Hanlon are fill-in news presenters.\n\n=== Sport ===\nSport presenters have included:\n* [[Michael Slater]] (Sunday: 2009 \u2013 2010)\n* [[Tim Gilbert (journalist)|Tim Gilbert]] (Saturday: 2009 \u2013 2010)\n* [[Tim Gilbert (journalist)|Tim Gilbert]] (2010\u2013September 2014)\n* [[Nathan Brown (Australian footballer born 1978)|Nathan Brown]] (September 2014 \u2013 December 2014)\n* [[Cameron Williams]] (2015 \u2013 2016)\n* Tom Steinfort (2016 \u2013 2017)\n* Peter Stefanovic (2016; 2018)\n* Clint Stanaway (2019)\n*Jayne Azzopardi (2020 \u2013 present)\n\n=== Weather ===\nIn December 2009, Felicity Whelan began presenting the weather on ''Weekend Today'' after she was chosen through the weekend weather competition, Whelan also filled in for [[Steven Jacobs (television presenter)|Steven Jacobs]] on ''Today''.\nHowever, in April 2010, main fill-in weather presenter, [[Emma Freedman]] replaced Whelan who joined [[Network Ten]]. Due to budget cuts at the Nine Network, Freedman was made redundant in late 2014. In 2015, [[Natalia Cooper]] was appointed as weather presenter. In December 2016, Steve Jacobs announced that he would be leaving ''Today'' to join ''Weekend Today'' as weather presenter. In March 2019, it was announced that ''[[Nine News]]'' reporter Tim Davies would join the team as weather presenter. In December 2019, Lauren Phillips was announced as ''Weekend Today'' weather presenter replacing Tim Davies who was promoted to ''[[Today (Australian TV program)|Today]]'' weather presenter.\n\nWeather presenters have included:\n* Felicity Whelan (2009 \u2013 2010)\n* [[Emma Freedman]] (2010 \u2013 2014)\n* [[Natalia Cooper]] (2015 \u2013 2016)\n* [[Steven Jacobs (television presenter)|Steve Jacobs]] (2017 \u2013 2018)\n* Tim Davies (2019)\n* Lauren Phillips (2019 \u2013 present)\n\n=== Entertainment ===\nIn February 2009, [[Michele Mahone]] joined ''Weekend Today'' as Hollywood Gossip reporter where she reported on the latest entertainment news. She remained with the show until September 2013 due to the show going in 'another direction'. That other direction was Susanne Messara who presented the latest entertainment news from the couch. This idea failed and media personality Giselle Ugarte was appointed entertainment presenter situated again in Hollywood. In 2015, Daily Telegraph columnist Elle Halliwell was appointed entertainment presenter replacing Ugarte. Halliwell along with the entertainment segments were removed shortly after.\n\nEntertainment presenters have included:\n* [[Michele Mahone]] (2009 \u2013 2013)\n* Susanne Messara (2013 \u2013 2014)\n* Gisele Ugarte (2014)\n* Elle Halliwell (2015)\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Australian television series]]\n* [[List of programs broadcast by Nine Network]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://www.9now.com.au/today}}\n\n{{TodayPresenters}}\n{{News & Current Affairs in Australia}}\n{{Nine Network programming}}\n{{AustralianWeekendBreakfastShows}}\n\n[[Category:Nine News|*]]\n[[Category:2009 Australian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2000s Australian television series]]\n[[Category:2010s Australian television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Sydney]]\n", "name_user": "Ellisam", "label": "safe", "comment": "date was wrong", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weekend_Today_(Australian_TV_program)"}
{"title_page": "Parents Just Don't Understand", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Parents Just Don't Understand\n| cover      = Parents Just Dont Understand.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[DJ Jazzy Jeff & The Fresh Prince]]\n| album      = [[He's the DJ, I'm the Rapper]]\n| released   = February 17, 1988\n| format     = [[12\" Vinyl]]\n| recorded   = 1987\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Golden age hip hop]], [[comedy hip hop]]\n| length     = {{unbulleted list|{{Duration|m=4|s=13}} (Radio Edit)|{{Duration|m=5|s=35}} (Album Version)}}\n| label      = [[Jive Records|Jive]]\n| writer     = Harris, Smith, Townes\n| producer   = Harris, Smith, Townes, New\n| prev_title = Brand New Funk\n| prev_year  = 1987\n| next_title = [[A Nightmare on My Street]]\n| next_year  = 1988\n| misc       = {{Audio sample\n | type = single\n | file = DJ Jazzy Jeff & The Fresh Prince - Parents Just Don't Understand.ogg\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Parents Just Don't Understand'''\" is the second single from [[DJ Jazzy Jeff & The Fresh Prince]]'s second studio album, ''[[He's the DJ, I'm the Rapper]]''. The song won a [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Performance]] at the [[1989 Grammy Awards]], one of the two songs to do so before the award was discontinued in 1991. It peaked at #12 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>http://www.allmusic.com/artist/dj-jazzy-jeff-the-fresh-prince-mn0000948022/awards</ref> The song was released as a single in spring 1988. The song was referenced several times in the [[television show]] ''[[The Fresh Prince Of Bel-Air]]''. The song was ranked #96 on VH1's 100 Greatest Songs of Hip Hop, and the music video was featured in the 2003 film ''[[Malibu's Most Wanted]].''\n\n==Premise==\nThe song's two major verses involve [[Will Smith|The Fresh Prince]]'s problems with his own parents. The first verse is a recollection of when he went school-shopping with his whole family, including his brother and their younger sister, at the [[The Gallery at Market East|Gallery Mall]]. The Prince's mother bought him a whole wardrobe that was way against his style, getting \"Zips\" shoes instead of [[Adidas]]...along with [[bell-bottoms]], reversible slacks, a plaid shirt with a butterfly collar, and the like. He suffered the inevitable on his first day at school. \n\nThe second verse was of him taking the family [[Porsche]] out for a spin - despite having no driver's license - while his parents were on vacation. He picks up a beautiful girl and goes to McDonald's. The Prince floors it, but gets pulled over for speeding...and discovers the beauty he picked up is a [[tween]] runaway. He gets arrested, and the Porsche is impounded. His parents cut short their vacation to bail him out, and issue severe physical discipline on the drive home.\n\n==Cover versions==\nIn late 2001, a [[Cover version|cover]] of the song was recorded by [[Lil' Romeo]], [[3LW]], and [[Nick Cannon]], which appears on the ''[[Jimmy Neutron: Boy Genius (film)|Jimmy Neutron: Boy Genius]]'' soundtrack. A video was made with cameo appearances from [[Vanessa L. Williams]] and [[Whoopi Goldberg]].\n\nThe song was also used by young [[Tupac Shakur]] in a music video he made with Smith's future wife [[Jada Pinkett]]. Shakur and Pinkett had been attending the [[Baltimore School for the Arts]]. The song was covered by [[Amy Poehler]] in the second season premiere of [[Parks and Recreation]]. In 2007 T-Squad covered the song on their only album \"T-Squad\".\n\n==Track listing==\n; 7\" Vinyl\n# \"Parents Just Don't Understand\" \u2013 4:13\n# \"Parents Just Don't Understand\" (Instrumental) \u2013 4:06\n\n; 12\" Vinyl\n# \"Parents Just Don't Understand\" (Danny D Mix) \u2013 6:20\n# \"Parents Just Don't Understand\" (Original 7\" Version) \u2013 5:13\n# \"Live At Union Square, November 1986\" \u2013 4:03\n\n; American 12\" Vinyl\n# \"Parents Just Don't Understand\" (Extended Mix) \u2013 5:27\n# \"Parents Just Don't Understand\" (Single Edit) \u2013 4:13\n# \"Parents Just Don't Understand\" (Instrumental) \u2013 4:06\n# \"Live At Union Square, November 1986\" \u2013 4:03\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1988)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|49|artist=DJ Jazzy Jeff & The Fresh Prince|song=Parents Just Don't Understand}}\n|-\n|Canada Top Singles ([[RPM (magazine)|RPM]])\n|align=\"center\"|28\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|13|artist=DJ Jazzy Jeff & The Fresh Prince|song=Parents Just Don't Understand}}\n|-\n|UK Singles ([[The Official Charts Company]])\n|align=\"center\"|87\n|-\n|U.S. [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]\n|align=\"center\"|12\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]]\n|align=\"center\"|10\n|-\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|type=single|region=United States|artist=DJ Jazzy Jeff & Fresh Prince|title=Parents Just Don't Understand|award=Gold|relyear=1988|certyear=1989|salesamount=500,000|refname=riaa}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DJ Jazzy Jeff & the Fresh Prince}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{YouTube|jW3PFC86UNI|Music video}}\n\n[[Category:1988 singles]]\n[[Category:1988 songs]]\n[[Category:DJ Jazzy Jeff & The Fresh Prince songs]]\n[[Category:3LW songs]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Best Rap Performance]]\n[[Category:Songs written by DJ Jazzy Jeff]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Will Smith]]\n[[Category:Novelty songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Parents Just Don't Understand\n| cover      = Parents Just Dont Understand.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[DJ Jazzy Jeff & The Fresh Prince]]\n| album      = [[He's the DJ, I'm the Rapper]]\n| released   = February 17, 1988\n| format     = [[12\" Vinyl]]\n| recorded   = 1987\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Golden age hip hop]], [[comedy hip hop]]\n| length     = {{unbulleted list|{{Duration|m=4|s=13}} (Radio Edit)|{{Duration|m=5|s=35}} (Album Version)}}\n| label      = [[Jive Records|Jive]]\n| writer     = Harris, Smith, Townes\n| producer   = Harris, Smith, Townes, New\n| prev_title = Brand New Funk\n| prev_year  = 1987\n| next_title = [[A Nightmare on My Street]]\n| next_year  = 1988\n| misc       = {{Audio sample\n | type = single\n | file = DJ Jazzy Jeff & The Fresh Prince - Parents Just Don't Understand.ogg\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Parents Just Don't Understand'''\" is the second single from [[DJ Jazzy Jeff & The Fresh Prince]]'s second studio album, ''[[He's the DJ, I'm the Rapper]]''. The song won a [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Performance]] at the [[1989 Grammy Awards]], one of the two songs to do so before the award was discontinued in 1991. It peaked at #12 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>http://www.allmusic.com/artist/dj-jazzy-jeff-the-fresh-prince-mn0000948022/awards</ref> The song was released as a single in spring 1988. The song was referenced several times in the [[television show]] ''[[The Fresh Prince Of Bel-Air]]''. The song was ranked #96 on VH1's 100 Greatest Songs of Hip Hop, and the music video was featured in the 2003 film ''[[Malibu's Most Wanted]].''\n\n==Premise==\nThe song's two major verses involve [[Will Smith|The Fresh Prince]]'s problems with his own parents. The first verse is a recollection of when he went school-shopping with his whole family, including his brother and their younger sister, at the [[The Gallery at Market East|Gallery Mall]]. The Prince's mother bought him a whole wardrobe that was way against his style, getting \"Zips\" shoes instead of [[Adidas]]...along with [[bell-bottoms]], reversible slacks, a plaid shirt with a butterfly collar, and the like. He suffered the inevitable on his first day at school. \n\nThe second verse was of him taking the family [[Porsche]] out for a spin - despite having no driver's license - while his parents were on vacation. He picks up a beautiful girl and goes to McDonald's. The Prince floors it, but gets pulled over for speeding...and discovers the beauty he picked up is a [[tween]] runaway. He gets arrested, and the Porsche is impounded. His parents cut short their vacation to bail him out, and issue severe physical discipline on the drive home.\n\n==Cover versions==\nIn late 2001, a [[Cover version|cover]] of the song was recorded by [[Lil' Romeo]], [[3LW]], and [[Nick Cannon]], which appears on the ''[[Jimmy Neutron: Boy Genius (film)|Jimmy Neutron: Boy Genius]]'' soundtrack. A video was made with cameo appearances from [[Vanessa L. Williams]] and [[Whoopi Goldberg]].\n\nThe song was also used by young [[Tupac Shakur]] in a music video he made with Smith's future wife [[Jada Pinkett]]. Shakur and Pinkett had been attending the [[Baltimore School for the Arts]]. The song was covered by [[Amy Poehler]] in the second season premiere of [[Parks and Recreation]]. In 2007 T-Squad covered the song on their only album \"T-Squad\".\n\n==Track listing==\n; 7\" Vinyl\n# \"Parents Just Don't Understand\" \u2013 4:13\n# \"Parents Just Don't Understand\" (Instrumental) \u2013 4:06\n\n; 12\" Vinyl\n# \"Parents Just Don't Understand\" (Danny D Mix) \u2013 6:20\n# \"Parents Just Don't Understand\" (Original 7\" Version) \u2013 5:13\n# \"Live At Union Square, November 1986\" \u2013 4:03\n\n; American 12\" Vinyl\n# \"Parents Just Don't Understand\" (Extended Mix) \u2013 5:27\n# \"Parents Just Don't Understand\" (Single Edit) \u2013 4:13\n# \"Parents Just Don't Understand\" (Instrumental) \u2013 4:06\n# \"Live At Union Square, November 1986\" \u2013 4:03\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1988)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|49|artist=DJ Jazzy Jeff & The Fresh Prince|song=Parents Just Don't Understand}}\n|-\n|Canada Top Singles ([[RPM (magazine)|RPM]])\n|align=\"center\"|28\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|13|artist=DJ Jazzy Jeff & The Fresh Prince|song=Parents Just Don't Understand}}\n|-\n|UK Singles ([[The Official Charts Company]])\n|align=\"c