{"title_page": "DoYaThing", "text_new": "{{short description|Gorillaz song}}\n{{for|similarly titled songs|Do Ya Thang (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = DoYaThing\n| cover      = Gorillaz_-_DoYaThing_cover.png\n| alt        = From left to right: James Murphy as a monkey in a karate outfit, 2D in a black outfit wearing a hat, Murdoc Niccals dribbling a basketball at the waist level, and Andre 3000 wearing a black mask\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Gorillaz]] featuring [[James Murphy (electronic musician)|James Murphy]] and [[Andr\u00e9 3000]]\n| album      =\n| released   = {{Start date|2012|2|23|df=yes}}\n| format     = {{Flatlist|\n*[[Gramophone record|10-inch]]\n*[[CD single|CD]]\n*[[Music download|download]]\n}}\n| recorded   = Fall 2011 in London<ref name=\"p4k\" />\n| studio     =\n| genre      =\n| length     = {{plainlist|\n*4:26 <small>(radio edit)</small>\n*13:04 <small>(full version)</small>\n}}\n| label      = {{Flatlist|\n*[[Converse (shoe company)|Converse]]\n*[[EMI Records|EMI]]\n}}\n| writer     = {{Flatlist|\n* [[Damon Albarn]]\n* [[Andr\u00e9 3000|Andr\u00e9 Benjamin]]\n* [[James Murphy (electronic musician)|James Murphy]]\n}}\n| producer   = {{Flatlist|\n* Damon Albarn\n* Andr\u00e9 3000\n* James Murphy\n}}\n| chronology = [[Gorillaz]]\n| prev_title = [[Revolving Doors (Gorillaz song)|Revolving Doors]]/[[Amarillo (Gorillaz song)|Amarillo]]\n| prev_year  = 2011\n| next_title = [[Saturnz Barz]]\n| next_year  = 2017\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[James Murphy (electronic musician)|James Murphy]]\n | type       = singles\n | prev_title =\n | prev_year  =\n | title      = DoYaThing\n | year       = 2012\n | next_title =\n | next_year  =\n}}\n{{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Andr\u00e9 3000]]\n | type       = singles\n | prev_title = [[I Do (Young Jeezy song)|I Do]]\n | prev_year  = 2012\n | title      = DoYaThing\n | year       = 2012\n | next_title = [[Sorry (T.I. song)|Sorry]]\n | next_year  = 2012\n}}\n{{External music video|{{YouTube|yNeF30RverQ|\"DoYaThing\"}}}}\n}}\n\"'''DoYaThing'''\" is a song by [[alternative rock]] [[virtual band]] [[Gorillaz]], featuring [[LCD Soundsystem]] frontman [[James Murphy (electronic musician)|James Murphy]] and [[Andr\u00e9 3000]] of [[Outkast]]. The song was released on 23 February 2012. It was commissioned by [[Converse (shoe company)|Converse]] as a part of their \"Three Artists. One Song\" project where three artists collaborate on a track. The song is also the starting point for a limited edition [[Chuck Taylor All-Stars]] collection designed by Gorillaz artist [[Jamie Hewlett]]. The shoe designs feature artwork from other projects related to Gorillaz.<ref name=\"ew\">{{cite web |url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2012/02/09/gorillaz-converse-song-andre-3000-james-murphy/ |title=Gorillaz team up with Andre 3000 and James Murphy for Converse track 'DoYaThing'&nbsp;\u2013 EXCLUSIVE |author=Kyle Anderson |date=9 February 2012 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=1 March 2012}}</ref> It was released in two different versions: the approximately 4-and-a-half-minute radio edit, and the explicit 13-minute version.<ref name=\"gorillaz\" /> The former was released as a free download on Converse's website,<ref name=\"billboard\" /> while the latter was released for streaming on Gorillaz's website.<ref name=\"gorillaz\">{{cite web |url=http://gorillaz.com/doyathing/ |title=Gorillaz + Andre 3000 + James Murphy: Still Just Doing Their Thing |publisher=[[Gorillaz]] website |accessdate=4 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306084947/http://gorillaz.com/doyathing/ |archive-date=6 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The cover features a baboon representing Murphy and a masked figure representing Andr\u00e9 3000, referencing the single cover for \"I'm a Goner\" by [[Matt and Kim]].<ref name=\"ew\" /><ref name=\"gorillaz\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/02/09/gorillaz-do-ya-thing_n_1265377.html |title=Gorillaz, Andre 3000 And James Murphy's 'Do Ya Thing' For Converse |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |author=Mallika Rose |date=9 February 2012 |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Background and recording==\n{{multiple image\n<!-- Essential parameters -->\n| align = left\n| direction = vertical\n| width = 125\n\n<!-- Image 1 -->\n| image1 = Damon Albarn live29.07.2013 in Rome 4.JPG\n| width1 = 150\n| alt1 = A man holds a microphone with his left hand and puts his right hand up.\n| caption1 = Damon Albarn\n| link1 = Damon Albarn\n\n<!-- Image 2 -->\n| image2 = James Murphy by Sachyn Mital.jpg\n| width2 = 150\n| alt2 = A man wearing headphones uses a digital turntable.\n| caption2 = James Murphy\n| link2 = James Murphy (electronic musician)\n\n| image3 = Andre Benjamin crop.jpg\n| width3 = 100\n| alt3 = A man speaks to a microphone at the San Diego Comic Con.\n| caption3 = Andr\u00e9 3000\n|link3 = Andr\u00e9 3000\n}} The idea for \"DoYaThing\" started when Converse asked Gorillaz creators [[Damon Albarn]] and [[Jamie Hewlett]] to design an exclusive shoe collection that would feature artwork influenced by Gorillaz. After the design was finished, Converse and [[Cornerstone (agency)|Cornerstone]], the company that promotes products from the \"Three Artists. One Song.\" campaign, persuaded Albarn to broaden their partnership to a collaborative track. Albarn accepted, and invited [[LCD Soundsystem]] leader [[James Murphy (electronic musician)|James Murphy]] and [[Outkast]] member [[Andr\u00e9 3000]], who both signed on.<ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/504508/gorillazjames-murphyandre-3000s-converse-track-the-story-behind-the-song |title=Gorillaz/James Murphy/Andre 3000's Converse Track: The Story Behind The Song |author=Jason Lipshutz |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=21 February 2012 |accessdate=3 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nInstead of recording the song by sending it via [[e-mail]], as Murphy initially feared, the three met in Albarn's [[London]] studio to record the track.<ref name=\"p4k\">{{cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/news/45518-damon-albarn-and-james-murphy-talk-converse-collaboration-with-andre-3000/ |title=Damon Albarn and James Murphy Talk Converse Collaboration With Andr\u00e9 3000 |author=Ryan Dombal |date=23 February 2012 |publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]] |accessdate=3 March 2012}}</ref> Despite the three only knowing each other through their music, Albarn described the experience of meeting them as \"very natural\", saying \"We were comfortable with each other immediately.\" The song was written and recorded over three days, with the 13-minute version being recorded on the last one.<ref name=\"billboard\" /><ref name=\"p4k\" />\n\nSpeaking further about the collaboration Albarn said: \"I only knew these guys through their work before we got together. The 12-minute version represents what we did over three days-- it's quite an insane progression. That version evolved out of just a drum beat and a [[guitar]], and then Andr\u00e9 just started going, and there was no sense that he was ever going to stop, it was a very exhilarating ride. It's live: I'm playing guitar, the [[drum machine]] is going, James is playing [[Bass guitar|bass]], and Andr\u00e9 just goes off. And what he's saying just gets more and more ridiculous. It finished on its own will, we really had nothing to do with it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/45518-damon-albarn-and-james-murphy-talk-converse-collaboration-with-andre-3000/|title=Damon Albarn and James Murphy Talk Converse Collaboration With Andr\u00e9 3000|website=Pitchfork|accessdate=Aug 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n{{Listen\n| left\n| filename=Gorillaz - DoYaThing.ogg\n| title=\"DoYaThing\"\n| description=This 26-second sample of the song highlights Murphy's hook and Andr\u00e9 3000's singing.\n}}\nThe song features Albarn playing [[guitar]], Murphy playing [[bass guitar]], and Andr\u00e9 3000 rapping with a [[drum machine]] in the background. The song's lyrics are abstract, as Albarn said it was hard to write them based on a shoe.<ref name=\"p4k\" /> Albarn starts the song rapping in his \"[[2D (Gorillaz)|2D]] voice\", ad-libbed. Murphy then sings the chorus in [[falsetto]] with an [[organ (instrument)|organ]] playing in the background. His vocals on the song have been likened to Alexis Taylor of [[Hot Chip]].<ref name=\"nme\" /> Two minutes into the song,<ref name=\"md\" /> Andr\u00e9 3000 starts rapping around the title line \"''Do ya damn thang.''\"<ref name=\"nme\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spinner.com/2012/02/22/gorillaz-andre-3000-james-murphy/ |title=Gorillaz 'DoYaThing': Andre 3000 and James Murphy Team With Cartoon Band for Converse |author=Kenneth Partridge |date=22 February 2012 |publisher=[[Spinner (website)|Spinner]] |accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe song was originally only a [[drum beat]] and a guitar. Because of this, the 13 minute version of the song was seen as a progression of the song by Albarn. It was recorded on the trio's last day of recording together. This version of ''DoYaThing'' continues from the 5 minute edit, with Andr\u00e9 3000 improvising and the song building to a noisy, [[krautrock]]-esque climax, reminiscent of Murphy's former band, LCD Soundsystem's \"[[Crass]] version\" of \"[[Yeah (LCD Soundsystem song)|Yeah]]\".<ref name=\"p4k\" /> During the five-minute climax, Andr\u00e9 3000 repeatedly yells the phrase \"I'm the shit\", followed by boasts like \"The Moon is jealous of me, The Sun is jealous of me\".<ref name=\"p4k\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://stereogum.com/959231/hear-the-13-minute-version-of-doyathing/mp3s/ |title=Hear The 13 Minute Version Of \"DoYaThing\" |date=24 February 2012 |accessdate=3 March 2012 |publisher=[[Stereogum]]}}</ref> The lyric was based on an encounter Albarn had with a bicycling by [[Brian Eno]] (Whom Albarn would later collaborate with on his debut solo album ''[[Everyday Robots]]'', on the tracks \"[[You and Me (Damon Albarn song)|You and Me]]\" and \"[[Heavy Seas of Love]]\") who responded to Albarn's \"How's it going Brian?\" by telling him \"Everything I'm working on is coming out great.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nmmatters.com/2013/05/james-murphy-of-lcd-soundsystem-at-red.html|title=James Murphy of LCD Soundsystem at Red Bull Academy, May 27|accessdate=Aug 20, 2019}}</ref> The three likened the response to saying \"Oh, it's great&nbsp;\u2013 I'm the shit.\" Albarn and Murphy both thought this version was a good representation of their work on the song; Albarn stated \"It's a nice narrative.\"<ref name=\"p4k\" />\n\n==Reception==\nThe song received positive reviews from music critics. Jon Dolan of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' gave the song three and a half stars out of five, writing \"Putting this many visionary types in one studio could\u2019ve made for a mess, but they lock in for a three-man weave&nbsp;\u2013 like the [[Larry Bird|Bird]]-[[Kevin McHale (basketball)|McHale]]-[[Robert Parish|Parish]] of avant-R&B.\"<ref name=\"rs\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/songreviews/doyathing-20120217 |title=DoYaThing Song Review |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |author=Jon Dolan |date=17 February 2012 |accessdate=1 March 2012}}</ref> ''[[The Michigan Daily]]'' criticized the [[beat (music)|beat]] as \"awkward\", Albarn's [[rap (music)|rapping]] as a \"fail[ure]\", and Murphy's chorus as \"weird and warbling\". However, the newspaper highly praised Andr\u00e9 3000's rapping, as they stated \"His lines are sick, his pacing is Gatling-gun quick, and he dominates in comparison [to Murphy and Albarn].\" As a whole, they gave the track three and a half stars out of five.<ref name=\"md\">{{cite web |url=http://www.michigandaily.com/arts/single-review-doyathang |title=Single Review: 'DoYaThing' barely manages to do its thing |work=[[The Michigan Daily]] |author=Elliot Alpern |date=22 February 2012 |accessdate=1 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn a positive review, [[NME]] complimented the duo of Damon Albarn and Andr\u00e9 3000. Writer Priya Elan stated \"Murphy makes a brilliant backstage star, but the song is all about the Damon and Andre moment.\"<ref name=\"nme\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/blog/index.php?blog=1&title=title_517&more=1&c=1&tb=1&pb=1 |title=Gorillaz, James Murphy, Andre 3000, 'DoYaThing'&nbsp;\u2013 Review |work=[[NME]] |author=Priya Elan |date=12 February 2012 |accessdate=1 March 2012}}</ref> [[Beats Per Minute (website)|Beats Per Minute]] named the track the best one so far of the \"Three Artists. One Song.\" project, calling it \"a potent reminder of the power of collaborative music.\" They gave the track 9 out of 10, saying the artists \"play off of each other remarkably well.\"<ref name=\"bpm\">{{cite web |url=http://www.beatsperminute.com/reviews/track-review-gorillaz-doyathing-feat-andre-3000-and-james-murphy |title=Track review Gorillaz DoYaThing feat. Andre 3000 and James Murphy |publisher=[[Beats Per Minute (website)|Beats Per Minute]] |author=Brendan Frank |date=24 February 2012 |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref> ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' wrote that the track was \"one of the best collaborations we've heard in a while,\" saying it \"merges three genre pools, but still highlights the traits distinctive to each musician.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/02/23/doyathing-gorillaz-andre-3000-james-murphy_n_1295056.html |title='DoYaThing': Gorillaz, Andre 3000 and James Murphy Release Collaboration For Converse (AUDIO) |date=23 February 2012 |work=The Huffington Post |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe video for \"DoYaThing\" was directed by Jamie Hewlett and was released on 29 February 2012. The video uses a mix of 2-dimension and [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] characters combined with live-action footage. The house used for filming is 212 Hammersmith Grove, in Hammersmith, West London.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/viral-videos/502982/gorillaz-animation-live-action-doyathing-video-watch |title=Gorillaz Animation + Live Action = 'DoYaThing' Video: Watch |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |author=Jillian Mapes |date=29 February 2012 |accessdate=3 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boston.com/ae/music/blog/2012/03/gorillaz_feat_a.html |title=Gorillaz feat. Andre 3000 and James Murphy 'DoYaThing' |author=Mawuse Ziagbe |date=2 March 2012 |publisher=[[Boston.com]] |accessdate=3 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe music video opens to a video of a [[crocodile]] scaring a herd of [[antelope]]. It then cuts to a scene where [[2-D (character)|2-D]] wakes up and changes clothes in 212 Wobble Street, London, SW21 7QJ. He exits his room and checks another one, finding other band member [[Noodle (character)|Noodle]] fast asleep. After that, he looks in a bathroom and finds a masked figure representing Andr\u00e9 3000,<ref name=\"ew\" /><ref name=\"vid\" /> surrounded by light blue-skinned \"sweat collectors\". Disgusted, 2-D looks in another room that turns out to be shrouded in complete darkness with the sounds of sheep, chickens and a man crying, which in turn is a reference to a [[Motorola]] commercial which band member [[Murdoc Niccals|Murdoc]] appeared in.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nUfE33LjR5Q|title=Gorillaz - Motorola Sting (HD)|accessdate=Aug 20, 2019|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref> Murdoc then scares 2-D by popping up in the room, and he proceeds to go down the stairs using a [[stair lift]] as 2-D goes to the living room as the ''[[Doncamatic]]'' submarine makes a cameo appearance behind him, and finds a previous character from the third album ''[[Plastic Beach]]'' named the Boogeyman reading a newspaper (while the ''[[Dare (song)|DARE]]'' music video plays on the TV).<ref name=\"gorillaz\" /><ref name=\"vid\" /> He goes down to the kitchen and opens a cabinet, only to find the masked figure stuffed inside it. Calmly shutting the door on him, he cooks toast and puts it on his plate along with, without realizing, a human ear from a bowl of them near the toaster. 2-D then opens a refrigerator and finds the masked figure stuffed inside it, who gives 2-D a carton of milk and a jar of jam. At the dining table, he reads a fictional newspaper comic entitled ''The Gorillaz'', showing comics called \"The Funnies\" which features a comic of Murdoc hugging 2-D. Murdoc, having finally finished going down the stairs, goes up to 2-D and hits him with a Gorillaz Converse shoe, unlike the comic. 2-D decides against eating the toast upon realising that it has an ear on it, turns off the radio (which also cuts the song) and leaves the house, while Murdoc starts a transmission from his radio station, playing the intro to the Gorillaz song ''[[5/4 (Gorillaz song)|5/4]]''. Once outside, he receives a [[Eviction#Notice|notice of eviction]] from a baboon [[mail carrier|mailman]] representing James Murphy, and smiles, looking relieved. The car from the music video of ''[[Stylo (song)|Stylo]]'' is \"parked\" outside. The camera points up, revealing a still-giant [[Russel Hobbs|Russel]] sleeping on the roof of the house and the remains of the windmill island (nicknamed \"The Slowboat\") from the ''[[Feel Good Inc.]]'' and ''[[El Ma\u00f1ana (song)|El Ma\u00f1ana]]'' music videos floating in the sky.<ref name=\"gorillaz\" /><ref name=\"vid\">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yNeF30RverQ |title=\"DoYaThing\" Official Video&nbsp;\u2013 Gorillaz featuring Andre 3000 and James Murphy |author=[[Jamie Hewlett]] |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=28 February 2012 |accessdate=4 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s3yCH5SKN_M |title=Gorillaz&nbsp;\u2013 El Manana (Remastered) |author=[[Parlophone]] |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=27 August 2008 |accessdate=11 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n;Promotional CD single\n# \"DoYaThing\" (radio edit) \u2013 4:26\n# \"DoYaThing\" (full-length version) \u2013 13:04\n\n;10\" Record Store Day vinyl\n# \"DoYaThing\" (full-length version) \u2013 13:04\n\n==Personnel==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*[[James Murphy (electronic musician)|James Murphy]] - vocals, bass guitar, synthesizer, keyboards, drums, production\n*[[Damon Albarn]] - vocals, synthesizer, keyboards, guitar, programming, production\n*[[Andre 3000]] - vocals, keyboards, synthesizer, production\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=33em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{YouTube|id=yNeF30RverQ|title=\"DoYaThing\" official video}}\n\n{{Gorillaz singles}}\n{{Andr\u00e9 3000}}\n\n[[Category:2012 songs]]\n[[Category:2012 singles]]\n[[Category:Funk songs]]\n[[Category:Gorillaz songs]]\n[[Category:Post-disco songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Damon Albarn]]\n[[Category:Songs written by James Murphy (electronic musician)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Andr\u00e9 3000]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Jamie Hewlett]]\n[[Category:Novelty songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Gorillaz song}}\n{{for|similarly titled songs|Do Ya Thang (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = DoYaThing\n| cover      = Gorillaz_-_DoYaThing_cover.png\n| alt        = From left to right: James Murphy as a monkey in a karate outfit, 2D in a black outfit wearing a hat, Murdoc Niccals dribbling a basketball at the waist level, and Andre 3000 wearing a black mask\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Gorillaz]] featuring [[James Murphy (electronic musician)|James Murphy]] and [[Andr\u00e9 3000]]\n| album      =\n| released   = {{Start date|2012|2|23|df=yes}}\n| format     = {{Flatlist|\n*[[Gramophone record|10-inch]]\n*[[CD single|CD]]\n*[[Music download|download]]\n}}\n| recorded   = Fall 2011 in London<ref name=\"p4k\" />\n| studio     =\n| genre      =\n| length     = {{plainlist|\n*4:26 <small>(radio edit)</small>\n*13:04 <small>(full version)</small>\n}}\n| label      = {{Flatlist|\n*[[Converse (shoe company)|Converse]]\n*[[EMI Records|EMI]]\n}}\n| writer     = {{Flatlist|\n* [[Damon Albarn]]\n* [[Andr\u00e9 3000|Andr\u00e9 Benjamin]]\n* [[James Murphy (electronic musician)|James Murphy]]\n}}\n| producer   = {{Flatlist|\n* Damon Albarn\n* Andr\u00e9 3000\n* James Murphy\n}}\n| chronology = [[Gorillaz]]\n| prev_title = [[Revolving Doors (Gorillaz song)|Revolving Doors]]/[[Amarillo (Gorillaz song)|Amarillo]]\n| prev_year  = 2011\n| next_title = [[Saturnz Barz]]\n| next_year  = 2017\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[James Murphy (electronic musician)|James Murphy]]\n | type       = singles\n | prev_title =\n | prev_year  =\n | title      = DoYaThing\n | year       = 2012\n | next_title =\n | next_year  =\n}}\n{{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Andr\u00e9 3000]]\n | type       = singles\n | prev_title = [[I Do (Young Jeezy song)|I Do]]\n | prev_year  = 2012\n | title      = DoYaThing\n | year       = 2012\n | next_title = [[Sorry (T.I. song)|Sorry]]\n | next_year  = 2012\n}}\n{{External music video|{{YouTube|yNeF30RverQ|\"DoYaThing\"}}}}\n}}\n\"'''DoYaThing'''\" is a song by [[alternative rock]] [[virtual band]] [[Gorillaz]], featuring [[LCD Soundsystem]] frontman [[James Murphy (electronic musician)|James Murphy]] and [[Andr\u00e9 3000]] of [[Outkast]]. The song was released on 23 February 2012. It was commissioned by [[Converse (shoe company)|Converse]] as a part of their \"Three Artists. One Song\" project where three artists collaborate on a track. The song is also the starting point for a limited edition [[Chuck Taylor All-Stars]] collection designed by Gorillaz artist [[Jamie Hewlett]]. The shoe designs feature artwork from other projects related to Gorillaz.<ref name=\"ew\">{{cite web |url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2012/02/09/gorillaz-converse-song-andre-3000-james-murphy/ |title=Gorillaz team up with Andre 3000 and James Murphy for Converse track 'DoYaThing'&nbsp;\u2013 EXCLUSIVE |author=Kyle Anderson |date=9 February 2012 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=1 March 2012}}</ref> It was released in two different versions: the approximately 4-and-a-half-minute radio edit, and the explicit 13-minute version.<ref name=\"gorillaz\" /> The former was released as a free download on Converse's website,<ref name=\"billboard\" /> while the latter was released for streaming on Gorillaz's website.<ref name=\"gorillaz\">{{cite web |url=http://gorillaz.com/doyathing/ |title=Gorillaz + Andre 3000 + James Murphy: Still Just Doing Their Thing |publisher=[[Gorillaz]] website |accessdate=4 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306084947/http://gorillaz.com/doyathing/ |archive-date=6 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The cover features a baboon representing Murphy and a masked figure representing Andr\u00e9 3000, referencing the single cover for \"I'm a Goner\" by [[Matt and Kim]].<ref name=\"ew\" /><ref name=\"gorillaz\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/02/09/gorillaz-do-ya-thing_n_1265377.html |title=Gorillaz, Andre 3000 And James Murphy's 'Do Ya Thing' For Converse |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |author=Mallika Rose |date=9 February 2012 |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Background and recording==\n{{multiple image\n<!-- Essential parameters -->\n| align = left\n| direction = vertical\n| width = 125\n\n<!-- Image 1 -->\n| image1 = Damon Albarn live29.07.2013 in Rome 4.JPG\n| width1 = 150\n| alt1 = A man holds a microphone with his left hand and puts his right hand up.\n| caption1 = Damon Albarn\n| link1 = Damon Albarn\n\n<!-- Image 2 -->\n| image2 = James Murphy by Sachyn Mital.jpg\n| width2 = 150\n| alt2 = A man wearing headphones uses a digital turntable.\n| caption2 = James Murphy\n| link2 = James Murphy (electronic musician)\n\n| image3 = Andre Benjamin crop.jpg\n| width3 = 100\n| alt3 = A man speaks to a microphone at the San Diego Comic Con.\n| caption3 = Andr\u00e9 3000\n|link3 = Andr\u00e9 3000\n}} The idea for \"DoYaThing\" started when Converse asked Gorillaz creators [[Damon Albarn]] and [[Jamie Hewlett]] to design an exclusive shoe collection that would feature artwork influenced by Gorillaz. After the design was finished, Converse and [[Cornerstone (agency)|Cornerstone]], the company that promotes products from the \"Three Artists. One Song.\" campaign, persuaded Albarn to broaden their partnership to a collaborative track. Albarn accepted, and invited [[LCD Soundsystem]] leader [[James Murphy (electronic musician)|James Murphy]] and [[Outkast]] member [[Andr\u00e9 3000]], who both signed on.<ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/504508/gorillazjames-murphyandre-3000s-converse-track-the-story-behind-the-song |title=Gorillaz/James Murphy/Andre 3000's Converse Track: The Story Behind The Song |author=Jason Lipshutz |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=21 February 2012 |accessdate=3 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nInstead of recording the song by sending it via [[e-mail]], as Murphy initially feared, the three met in Albarn's [[London]] studio to record the track.<ref name=\"p4k\">{{cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/news/45518-damon-albarn-and-james-murphy-talk-converse-collaboration-with-andre-3000/ |title=Damon Albarn and James Murphy Talk Converse Collaboration With Andr\u00e9 3000 |author=Ryan Dombal |date=23 February 2012 |publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]] |accessdate=3 March 2012}}</ref> Despite the three only knowing each other through their music, Albarn described the experience of meeting them as \"very natural\", saying \"We were comfortable with each other immediately.\" The song was written and recorded over three days, with the 13-minute version being recorded on the last one.<ref name=\"billboard\" /><ref name=\"p4k\" />\n\nSpeaking further about the collaboration Albarn said: \"I only knew these guys through their work before we got together. The 12-minute version represents what we did over three days-- it's quite an insane progression. That version evolved out of just a drum beat and a [[guitar]], and then Andr\u00e9 just started going, and there was no sense that he was ever going to stop, it was a very exhilarating ride. It's live: I'm playing guitar, the [[drum machine]] is going, James is playing [[Bass guitar|bass]], and Andr\u00e9 just goes off. And what he's saying just gets more and more ridiculous. It finished on its own will, we really had nothing to do with it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/45518-damon-albarn-and-james-murphy-talk-converse-collaboration-with-andre-3000/|title=Damon Albarn and James Murphy Talk Converse Collaboration With Andr\u00e9 3000|website=Pitchfork|accessdate=Aug 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n{{Listen\n| left\n| filename=Gorillaz - DoYaThing.ogg\n| title=\"DoYaThing\"\n| description=This 26-second sample of the song highlights Murphy's hook and Andr\u00e9 3000's singing.\n}}\nThe song features Albarn playing [[guitar]], Murphy playing [[bass guitar]], and Andr\u00e9 3000 rapping with a [[drum machine]] in the background. The song's lyrics are abstract, as Albarn said it was hard to write them based on a shoe.<ref name=\"p4k\" /> Albarn starts the song rapping in his \"[[2D (Gorillaz)|2D]] voice\", ad-libbed. Murphy then sings the chorus in [[falsetto]] with an [[organ (instrument)|organ]] playing in the background. His vocals on the song have been likened to Alexis Taylor of [[Hot Chip]].<ref name=\"nme\" /> Two minutes into the song,<ref name=\"md\" /> Andr\u00e9 3000 starts rapping around the title line \"''Do ya damn thang.''\"<ref name=\"nme\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spinner.com/2012/02/22/gorillaz-andre-3000-james-murphy/ |title=Gorillaz 'DoYaThing': Andre 3000 and James Murphy Team With Cartoon Band for Converse |author=Kenneth Partridge |date=22 February 2012 |publisher=[[Spinner (website)|Spinner]] |accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe song was originally only a [[drum beat]] and a guitar. Because of this, the 13 minute version of the song was seen as a progression of the song by Albarn. It was recorded on the trio's last day of recording together. This version of ''DoYaThing'' continues from the 5 minute edit, with Andr\u00e9 3000 improvising and the song building to a noisy, [[krautrock]]-esque climax, reminiscent of Murphy's former band, LCD Soundsystem's \"[[Crass]] version\" of \"[[Yeah (LCD Soundsystem song)|Yeah]]\".<ref name=\"p4k\" /> During the five-minute climax, Andr\u00e9 3000 repeatedly yells the phrase \"I'm the shit\", followed by boasts like \"The Moon is jealous of me, The Sun is jealous of me\".<ref name=\"p4k\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://stereogum.com/959231/hear-the-13-minute-version-of-doyathing/mp3s/ |title=Hear The 13 Minute Version Of \"DoYaThing\" |date=24 February 2012 |accessdate=3 March 2012 |publisher=[[Stereogum]]}}</ref> The lyric was based on an encounter Albarn had with a bicycling by [[Brian Eno]] (Whom Albarn would later collaborate with on his debut solo album ''[[Everyday Robots]]'', on the tracks \"[[You and Me (Damon Albarn song)|You and Me]]\" and \"[[Heavy Seas of Love]]\") who responded to Albarn's \"How's it going Brian?\" by telling him \"Everything I'm working on is coming out great.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nmmatters.com/2013/05/james-murphy-of-lcd-soundsystem-at-red.html|title=James Murphy of LCD Soundsystem at Red Bull Academy, May 27|accessdate=Aug 20, 2019}}</ref> The three likened the response to saying \"Oh, it's great&nbsp;\u2013 I'm the shit.\" Albarn and Murphy both thought this version was a good representation of their work on the song; Albarn stated \"It's a nice narrative.\"<ref name=\"p4k\" />\n\n==Reception==\nThe song received positive reviews from music critics. Jon Dolan of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' gave the song three and a half stars out of five, writing \"Putting this many visionary types in one studio could\u2019ve made for a mess, but they lock in for a three-man weave&nbsp;\u2013 like the [[Larry Bird|Bird]]-[[Kevin McHale (basketball)|McHale]]-[[Robert Parish|Parish]] of avant-R&B.\"<ref name=\"rs\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/songreviews/doyathing-20120217 |title=DoYaThing Song Review |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |author=Jon Dolan |date=17 February 2012 |accessdate=1 March 2012}}</ref> ''[[The Michigan Daily]]'' criticized the [[beat (music)|beat]] as \"awkward\", Albarn's [[rap (music)|rapping]] as a \"fail[ure]\", and Murphy's chorus as \"weird and warbling\". However, the newspaper highly praised Andr\u00e9 3000's rapping, as they stated \"His lines are sick, his pacing is Gatling-gun quick, and he dominates in comparison [to Murphy and Albarn].\" As a whole, they gave the track three and a half stars out of five.<ref name=\"md\">{{cite web |url=http://www.michigandaily.com/arts/single-review-doyathang |title=Single Review: 'DoYaThing' barely manages to do its thing |work=[[The Michigan Daily]] |author=Elliot Alpern |date=22 February 2012 |accessdate=1 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn a positive review, [[NME]] complimented the duo of Damon Albarn and Andr\u00e9 3000. Writer Priya Elan stated \"Murphy makes a brilliant backstage star, but the song is all about the Damon and Andre moment.\"<ref name=\"nme\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/blog/index.php?blog=1&title=title_517&more=1&c=1&tb=1&pb=1 |title=Gorillaz, James Murphy, Andre 3000, 'DoYaThing'&nbsp;\u2013 Review |work=[[NME]] |author=Priya Elan |date=12 February 2012 |accessdate=1 March 2012}}</ref> [[Beats Per Minute (website)|Beats Per Minute]] named the track the best one so far of the \"Three Artists. One Song.\" project, calling it \"a potent reminder of the power of collaborative music.\" They gave the track 9 out of 10, saying the artists \"play off of each other remarkably well.\"<ref name=\"bpm\">{{cite web |url=http://www.beatsperminute.com/reviews/track-review-gorillaz-doyathing-feat-andre-3000-and-james-murphy |title=Track review Gorillaz DoYaThing feat. Andre 3000 and James Murphy |publisher=[[Beats Per Minute (website)|Beats Per Minute]] |author=Brendan Frank |date=24 February 2012 |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref> ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' wrote that the track was \"one of the best collaborations we've heard in a while,\" saying it \"merges three genre pools, but still highlights the traits distinctive to each musician.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/02/23/doyathing-gorillaz-andre-3000-james-murphy_n_1295056.html |title='DoYaThing': Gorillaz, Andre 3000 and James Murphy Release Collaboration For Converse (AUDIO) |date=23 February 2012 |work=The Huffington Post |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe video for \"DoYaThing\" was directed by Jamie Hewlett and was released on 29 February 2012. The video uses a mix of 2-dimension and [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] characters combined with live-action footage. The house used for filming is 212 Hammersmith Grove, in Hammersmith, West London.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/viral-videos/502982/gorillaz-animation-live-action-doyathing-video-watch |title=Gorillaz Animation + Live Action = 'DoYaThing' Video: Watch |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |author=Jillian Mapes |date=29 February 2012 |accessdate=3 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boston.com/ae/music/blog/2012/03/gorillaz_feat_a.html |title=Gorillaz feat. Andre 3000 and James Murphy 'DoYaThing' |author=Mawuse Ziagbe |date=2 March 2012 |publisher=[[Boston.com]] |accessdate=3 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe music video opens to a video of a [[crocodile]] scaring a herd of [[antelope]]. It then cuts to a scene where [[2-D (character)|2-D]] wakes up and changes clothes in 212 Wobble Street, London, SW21 7QJ. He exits his room and checks another one, finding other band member [[Noodle (character)|Noodle]] fast asleep. After that, he looks in a bathroom and finds a masked figure representing Andr\u00e9 3000,<ref name=\"ew\" /><ref name=\"vid\" /> surrounded by light blue-skinned \"sweat collectors\". Disgusted, 2-D looks in another room that turns out to be shrouded in complete darkness with the sounds of sheep, chickens and a man crying, which in turn is a reference to a [[Motorola]] commercial which band member [[Murdoc Niccals|Murdoc]] appeared in.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nUfE33LjR5Q|title=Gorillaz - Motorola Sting (HD)|accessdate=Aug 20, 2019|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref> Murdoc then scares 2-D by popping up in the room, and he proceeds to go down the stairs using a [[stair lift]] as 2-D goes to the living room as the ''[[Doncamatic]]'' submarine makes a cameo appearance behind him, and finds a previous character from the third album ''[[Plastic Beach]]'' named the Boogeyman reading a newspaper (while the ''[[Dare (song)|DARE]]'' music video plays on the TV).<ref name=\"gorillaz\" /><ref name=\"vid\" /> He goes down to the kitchen and opens a cabinet, only to find the masked figure stuffed inside it. Calmly shutting the door on him, he cooks toast and puts it on his plate along with, without realizing, a human ear from a bowl of them near the toaster. 2-D then opens a refrigerator and finds the masked figure stuffed inside it, who gives 2-D a carton of milk and a jar of jam. At the dining table, he reads a fictional newspaper comic entitled ''The Gorillaz'', showing comics called \"The Funnies\" which features a comic of Murdoc hugging 2-D. Murdoc, having finally finished going down the stairs, goes up to 2-D and hits him with a Gorillaz Converse shoe, unlike the comic. 2-D decides against eating the toast upon realising that it has an ear on it, turns off the radio (which also cuts the song) and leaves the house, while Murdoc starts a transmission from his radio station, playing the intro to the Gorillaz song ''[[5/4 (Gorillaz song)|5/4]]''. Once outside, he receives a [[Eviction#Notice|notice of eviction]] from a baboon [[mail carrier|mailman]] representing James Murphy, and smiles, looking relieved. The car from the music video of ''[[Stylo (song)|Stylo]]'' is \"parked\" outside. The camera points up, revealing a still-giant [[Russel Hobbs|Russel]] sleeping on the roof of the house and the remains of the windmill island (nicknamed \"The Slowboat\") from the ''[[Feel Good Inc.]]'' and ''[[El Ma\u00f1ana (song)|El Ma\u00f1ana]]'' music videos floating in the sky.<ref name=\"gorillaz\" /><ref name=\"vid\">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yNeF30RverQ |title=\"DoYaThing\" Official Video&nbsp;\u2013 Gorillaz featuring Andre 3000 and James Murphy |author=[[Jamie Hewlett]] |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=28 February 2012 |accessdate=4 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s3yCH5SKN_M |title=Gorillaz&nbsp;\u2013 El Manana (Remastered) |author=[[Parlophone]] |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=27 August 2008 |accessdate=11 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n;Promotional CD single\n# \"DoYaThing\" (radio edit) \u2013 4:26\n# \"DoYaThing\" (full-length version) \u2013 13:04\n\n;10\" Record Store Day vinyl\n# \"DoYaThing\" (full-length version) \u2013 13:04\n\n==Personnel==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*[[James Murphy (electronic musician)|James Murphy]] - vocals, bass guitar, synthesizer, keyboards, drums, production\n*[[Damon Albarn]] - vocals, synthesizer, keyboards, guitar, programming, production\n*[[Andre 3000]] - vocals, keyboards, synthesizer, production\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=33em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{YouTube|id=yNeF30RverQ|title=\"DoYaThing\" official video}}\n\n{{Gorillaz singles}}\n{{Andr\u00e9 3000}}\n\n[[Category:2012 songs]]\n[[Category:2012 singles]]\n[[Category:Funk songs]]\n[[Category:Gorillaz songs]]\n[[Category:Post-disco songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Damon Albarn]]\n[[Category:Songs written by James Murphy (electronic musician)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Andr\u00e9 3000]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Jamie Hewlett]]\n", "name_user": "JordanPowers95", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(addedCategory:Novelty songsusingHotCat)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DoYaThing"}
{"title_page": "C Is For Cookie", "text_new": "[[File:Album c is for cookie cookies favourite songs.jpg|thumb|250px|Album cover of 'C Is For Cookie']]\n\n\"'''C Is For Cookie'''\", by [[Joe Raposo]], is a song performed by [[Cookie Monster]] ([[Frank Oz]]), a [[The Muppets|Muppet]] character from the preschool television series ''[[Sesame Street]]''. It was first performed in Season 3, although it had been released on ''[[The Muppet Alphabet Album]]''. Along with [[Kermit the Frog|Kermit]]'s \"[[Bein' Green]]\" and [[Ernie (Sesame Street)|Ernie]]'s \"[[Rubber Duckie]]\", it is one of the show's most recognizable songs. The original version was made in 1971 and was one of the few Sesame Street sketches directed by [[Jim Henson]].\n\n==History==\nAccording to the Muppet Central articles on the \"Songs from the Street Boxed Set, people really liked cookies. In 1971, [[Jim Henson]] and his performers teamed with [[Jerry Juhl]], Joe Raposo and [[Jeff Moss]] to write a [[sketch comedy|sketch]] on each letter of the [[alphabet]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.muppetcentral.com/articles/reviews/merchandise/songs_from_the_street.shtml |title=Muppet Central Articles - Songs from the Street Boxed Set|publisher=muppetcentral.com|accessdate=2008-05-19}}</ref> ''C Is For Cookie'' derives from this project.\nActress [[Candice Bergen]] sang the song when she visited ''Sesame Street''.\n\nA version was included on ''[[Sesame Street Fever]]''. A [[12\"]] promo single included disco remixes by [[Larry Levan]] and Roy Thode.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Cookie-Monster--Girls4--Pointer-Sisters-C-Is-For-Cookie-Pinball-Number-Count/release/185027 |title=Cookie Monster & The Girls / Pointer Sisters - C Is For Cookie|website=Discogs|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, a new operatic version was taped, featuring opera singer [[Marilyn Horne]] as [[Cleopatra]] in an Egyptian setting, with a pyramid made entirely out of cookies in the background. At the end of the song once \"Cleopatra\" is carried away out of sight, Cookie Monster appears in Egyptian attire and pulls a cookie off the pyramid, causing it to collapse with a huge crash while he eats it.\n\nSince then, several authorized and unauthorized versions of the song have been produced, including \"funky\" and \"sweet\" versions released on the 2003 record ''Cookie Monster & the Girls''.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.tunes.co.uk/tunes/featured/7506.html\n |title=C Is For Cookie - Cookie Monster & The Girls: Available at www.tunes.co.uk, the dance specialists\n|publisher=web.archive.org\n|accessdate=2008-05-19\n|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20051130094425/http://www.tunes.co.uk/tunes/featured/7506.html |archivedate = 2005-11-30}} (via [[Internet Archive]])</ref> Laura Pace's review of the home video ''[[Elmo's World: The Street We Live On]]'' noted 'the bizarreness of \"C is for Cookie\" done in ''[[Aida]]''-style opera'.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/04251/374529.stm\n|title=DVD/video shelves overflow with children's favorites and also-rans\n|publisher=www.post-gazette.com\n|accessdate=2008-05-19\n| first=Barbara\n| last=Vancheri\n| date=2004-09-07\n}}</ref> A short reprise of the song is also performed by Cookie Monster and the cast of ''Sesame Street'' on the 1975 album ''[[Bert & Ernie Sing-Along]]''. In addition, since the advent of YouTube, there have also been recordings of the song, regular and operatic, in reverse, under such titles as \"C Is For Cookie Reversed\" or \"Cheese Good For Fleas\" (which is what the phrase \"C is for Cookie\" sounds like dubbed backwards).\n\nConcerned about increased [[obesity]] rates in children, [[PBS]] announced that for its 36th season ''Sesame Street'' will have Cookie Monster promoting a more healthy approach to diet and nutrition. Cookie Monster listened to another character's song about cookies being a sometime food. At the end, Cookie Monster declared 'Now is sometimes!' and ate a cookie. This is nothing new however, as Cookie also did a rap music video called \"Healthy Food\" in the mid-1980s where he sings about healthy food like bread, fruits and vegetables with assorted muppets (most of whom are themselves singing, googly-eyed breads, fruits, and vegetables). Later, Haitian rapper [[Wyclef Jean]] accompanied Cookie Monster in a remake of the song. He also promoted the image of healthy eating in a song called \"A Cookie is a Sometime Food\", featuring Hoots the Owl.<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/1112985326449_58/?hub=Health\n |title       = CTV.ca: Cookie Monster advocates healthy eating\n |publisher   = www.ctv.ca\n |accessdate  = 2008-05-19\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070311003239/http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/1112985326449_58/?hub=Health\n |archivedate = 2007-03-11\n |df          = \n}}</ref>\n\nSheet music of the song has been published by the [[Hal Leonard Corporation]], and others. The toy \"Letter of the Day Cookie Jar\" features Cookie Monster saying a short phrase about each letter. For \"C\", he says \"C is for Cookie\". He also adds that a donut is a 'C' if you eat part of it.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{youtube|Ye8mB6VsUHw|C is for Cookie by Cookie Monster}}\n* Raposo, Joe: [https://web.archive.org/web/20050321092358/http://www.northern-pine.com/songs/cookie.html C Is For Cookie \u2013 lyrics]\n{{Sesame Street}}\n\n[[Category:Sesame Street songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Joe Raposo]]\n[[Category:1971 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about food]]\n[[Category:Novelty songs]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Album c is for cookie cookies favourite songs.jpg|thumb|250px|Album cover of 'C Is For Cookie']]\n\n\"'''C Is For Cookie'''\", by [[Joe Raposo]], is a song performed by [[Cookie Monster]] ([[Frank Oz]]), a [[The Muppets|Muppet]] character from the preschool television series ''[[Sesame Street]]''. It was first performed in Season 3, although it had been released on ''[[The Muppet Alphabet Album]]''. Along with [[Kermit the Frog|Kermit]]'s \"[[Bein' Green]]\" and [[Ernie (Sesame Street)|Ernie]]'s \"[[Rubber Duckie]]\", it is one of the show's most recognizable songs. The original version was made in 1971 and was one of the few Sesame Street sketches directed by [[Jim Henson]].\n\n==History==\nAccording to the Muppet Central articles on the \"Songs from the Street Boxed Set, people really liked cookies. In 1971, [[Jim Henson]] and his performers teamed with [[Jerry Juhl]], Joe Raposo and [[Jeff Moss]] to write a [[sketch comedy|sketch]] on each letter of the [[alphabet]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.muppetcentral.com/articles/reviews/merchandise/songs_from_the_street.shtml |title=Muppet Central Articles - Songs from the Street Boxed Set|publisher=muppetcentral.com|accessdate=2008-05-19}}</ref> ''C Is For Cookie'' derives from this project.\nActress [[Candice Bergen]] sang the song when she visited ''Sesame Street''.\n\nA version was included on ''[[Sesame Street Fever]]''. A [[12\"]] promo single included disco remixes by [[Larry Levan]] and Roy Thode.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Cookie-Monster--Girls4--Pointer-Sisters-C-Is-For-Cookie-Pinball-Number-Count/release/185027 |title=Cookie Monster & The Girls / Pointer Sisters - C Is For Cookie|website=Discogs|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, a new operatic version was taped, featuring opera singer [[Marilyn Horne]] as [[Cleopatra]] in an Egyptian setting, with a pyramid made entirely out of cookies in the background. At the end of the song once \"Cleopatra\" is carried away out of sight, Cookie Monster appears in Egyptian attire and pulls a cookie off the pyramid, causing it to collapse with a huge crash while he eats it.\n\nSince then, several authorized and unauthorized versions of the song have been produced, including \"funky\" and \"sweet\" versions released on the 2003 record ''Cookie Monster & the Girls''.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.tunes.co.uk/tunes/featured/7506.html\n |title=C Is For Cookie - Cookie Monster & The Girls: Available at www.tunes.co.uk, the dance specialists\n|publisher=web.archive.org\n|accessdate=2008-05-19\n|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20051130094425/http://www.tunes.co.uk/tunes/featured/7506.html |archivedate = 2005-11-30}} (via [[Internet Archive]])</ref> Laura Pace's review of the home video ''[[Elmo's World: The Street We Live On]]'' noted 'the bizarreness of \"C is for Cookie\" done in ''[[Aida]]''-style opera'.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/04251/374529.stm\n|title=DVD/video shelves overflow with children's favorites and also-rans\n|publisher=www.post-gazette.com\n|accessdate=2008-05-19\n| first=Barbara\n| last=Vancheri\n| date=2004-09-07\n}}</ref> A short reprise of the song is also performed by Cookie Monster and the cast of ''Sesame Street'' on the 1975 album ''[[Bert & Ernie Sing-Along]]''. In addition, since the advent of YouTube, there have also been recordings of the song, regular and operatic, in reverse, under such titles as \"C Is For Cookie Reversed\" or \"Cheese Good For Fleas\" (which is what the phrase \"C is for Cookie\" sounds like dubbed backwards).\n\nConcerned about increased [[obesity]] rates in children, [[PBS]] announced that for its 36th season ''Sesame Street'' will have Cookie Monster promoting a more healthy approach to diet and nutrition. Cookie Monster listened to another character's song about cookies being a sometime food. At the end, Cookie Monster declared 'Now is sometimes!' and ate a cookie. This is nothing new however, as Cookie also did a rap music video called \"Healthy Food\" in the mid-1980s where he sings about healthy food like bread, fruits and vegetables with assorted muppets (most of whom are themselves singing, googly-eyed breads, fruits, and vegetables). Later, Haitian rapper [[Wyclef Jean]] accompanied Cookie Monster in a remake of the song. He also promoted the image of healthy eating in a song called \"A Cookie is a Sometime Food\", featuring Hoots the Owl.<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/1112985326449_58/?hub=Health\n |title       = CTV.ca: Cookie Monster advocates healthy eating\n |publisher   = www.ctv.ca\n |accessdate  = 2008-05-19\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070311003239/http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/1112985326449_58/?hub=Health\n |archivedate = 2007-03-11\n |df          = \n}}</ref>\n\nSheet music of the song has been published by the [[Hal Leonard Corporation]], and others. The toy \"Letter of the Day Cookie Jar\" features Cookie Monster saying a short phrase about each letter. For \"C\", he says \"C is for Cookie\". He also adds that a donut is a 'C' if you eat part of it.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{youtube|Ye8mB6VsUHw|C is for Cookie by Cookie Monster}}\n* Raposo, Joe: [https://web.archive.org/web/20050321092358/http://www.northern-pine.com/songs/cookie.html C Is For Cookie \u2013 lyrics]\n{{Sesame Street}}\n\n[[Category:Sesame Street songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Joe Raposo]]\n[[Category:1971 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about food]]\n", "name_user": "JordanPowers95", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(addedCategory:Novelty songsusingHotCat)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C_Is_For_Cookie"}
{"title_page": "Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer", "text_new": "{{About||the film|Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer (film)|the ''Grey's Anatomy'' episode|Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer (Grey's Anatomy)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer\n| cover      = Single Elmo & Patsy-Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| caption    = Picture sleeve of 1984 release by [[Epic Records]] <small>(34-04703)</small>\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Elmo Shropshire|Elmo & Patsy]]\n| album      = Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer\n| B-side     = {{ubl|\"Christmas\" <small>(Elmo 'n' Patsy; Oink; Soundwaves)</small>|\"Percy, The Puny Poinsettia\" <small>([[Epic Records|Epic]])</small>}}\n| released   = 1979 <small>(Elmo 'n' Patsy)</small><br/>1982 <small>(Oink; Soundwaves)</small><br/>1984 <small>([[Epic Records|Epic]])</small>\n| format     = [[Single (music)|7-inch]]\n| recorded   = 1978\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Christmas music|Christmas]], [[country music|country]], [[Novelty song|novelty]], [[pop music|pop]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=30}} <small>(Elmo 'n' Patsy; Oink; Soundwaves)</small><br/>{{Duration|m=3|s=26}} <small>([[Epic Records|Epic]])</small>\n| label      = Elmo 'n' Patsy <small>2984</small><br/>Oink <small>2984</small><br />Soundwaves <small>4658</small><br />[[Epic Records|Epic]] <small>34-04703</small>\n| writer     = Randy Brooks\n| producer   = Gary Potterton\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\"'''Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer'''\" is a [[novelty song|novelty]] [[Christmas music|Christmas song]]. Written by Randy Brooks, the song was originally performed by the husband-and-wife duo of [[Elmo Shropshire|Elmo]] and Patsy Trigg Shropshire in 1979.\n\n==Synopsis==\nIn the lyrics, a [[Grandparent|grandmother]] is celebrating at a Christmas Eve party with her family when, while off her medication and [[alcohol intoxication|drunk]] on spiked [[eggnog]], she staggers outside into a [[Winter storm|snowstorm]] against the pleas of everyone in the room. She is found the next day, trampled; [[Santa Claus]] and his [[reindeer]] are determined to be the culprits when \"incriminating Claus marks\" are found on Grandma's back. The second and third verses describe the Christmas gathering where \"all the family's dressed in black\" to [[mourn]] her death and wonders if all the Christmas gifts they bought for her should be returned (the consensus is a firm yes). Christmas dinner otherwise goes on as normal, with a centerpiece of [[roast goose]], [[figgy pudding]] for dessert, and \"blue and silver candles\" to match Grandma's hairpiece; the newly widowed Grandpa seems completely unfazed by his wife's demise and spends the holiday \"[[Blue\u2013Gray Football Classic|watching football]], drinking beer and playing cards with Cousin Mel\" (who, while not stated as such in the lyrics, is an attractive and much younger woman in the music video and animated film). The [[Result|upshot]] is a warning to the listeners to beware, because \"a man who drives a sleigh and plays with elves\" should never receive a driver's license.\n\nIn the music video, in which Elmo plays both Grandma and Grandpa while Patsy plays Cousin Mel, Grandma survives the attack and makes a triumphant return through the chimney.\n\n==Releases==\nAccording to Brooks, he played the song while sitting in with Elmo and Patsy at the Hyatt [[Lake Tahoe]] in December 1978, and after the show they had him make a cassette of the song for them to learn. A year later, they were selling 45s of the song from the stage, with Elmo himself appearing in drag on the album cover as \"Grandma\".\n\nThe song was originally self-released in [[San Francisco]] by the Shropshires in 1979 on their own record label (on \"Elmo 'n' Patsy\" #2984), with the B-side titled \"Christmas\". Initial copies appeared on a cream-colored label, with a sketch of a pig clearly visible, at left. Once initial copies had sold out, later-pressed #2984 cream-colored 45 label copies retained the same pig sketch, but decided to both move the sketch, and add the word \"Oink\", to the top of the 45's label. Meanwhile, the duo's names were moved to the bottom of the label, below the song title. By the early 1980s, the song was becoming a seasonal hit, first on [[country music|country stations]] and then on [[Contemporary Hit Radio|Top 40 stations]]. Oink Records, still based in [[Windsor, California]], continued distribution of the 45 rpm record in the western U.S., with \"Nationwide Sound Distributors\" (NSD) of [[Nashville, Tennessee]], pressing and distributing the song on its [[Soundwaves Records]] in the eastern U.S., peaking at #92 on the country singles charts. In 1982, the duo both re-recorded and re-released the song as a single, again as Oink #2984. But this time, Oink chose to handle all nationwide product distribution themselves, ending the old NSD-Soundwaves agreement. Re-recorded Oink #2984 45 copies appeared on a white label, not a cream-colored label, however. That is the easiest way (aside from listening to the 45 itself) to differentiate between the original 1979 Oink #2984 recording and its now-much-more familiar, 1982 re-recording. An entire LP, named after their hit song, was also recorded in 1982, and was initially released as Oink #8223. In 1984, with the song now a big hit nationally, [[Sony Music Entertainment|CBS Records]] was interested in re-issuing both the 1982 Oink 45 re-recording, and the 1982 Oink LP. Soon after, [[Epic Records]] acquired the rights to both, from Elmo and Patsy. The Epic #04703 45 opted to replace the Oink 45's B-side, \"Christmas\", with a track from the LP, (\"Percy, the Puny [[Poinsettia]]\"). Epic's 1984 re-release of the 1982 Oink LP was a straight re-issue, on Epic #39931. By the end of 1984, it was reported that sales of \"Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer\" were, by record label: Oink: 50,000 45s sold; Soundwaves: 175,000 45s sold; Epic: 150,000 45s sold and 90,000 LPs sold. The Epic Records version charted at #64 on the country charts in 1998 and #48 in 1999.\n\nThe original version was released in the [[United Kingdom]] on [[Stiff Records]] (BUY 99) in 1980. It did not chart.\n\nOther releases by the original artist(s) would follow:\n\n*Following the Shropshires' divorce, Elmo re-recorded it solo in 1992 and again in 2000.\n*[[SonyBMG]] released ''Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer'' by [[Dr. Elmo]] in 2002. The 2002 re-recording is distinguished by a slightly different opening note in the chorus melody.\n*[[Madacy]] Records released a ''Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer'' gift tin (CD/DVD/Xmas stocking) by [[Dr. Elmo]] in 2007.\n*[[Time Life]] Records released ''Dr. Elmo's Bluegrass Christmas'' in 2010, which featured a bluegrass instrumental of \"Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer.\"\n\nA sequel, titled \"Grandpa's Gonna Sue the Pants Off of Santa\", in which Grandpa gets lawyers to fight Santa in court, was released by [[Elmo Shropshire]] on his album ''Dr. Elmo's Twisted Christmas'' (1992).\n\n==Covers==\nThe song has been recorded by other acts.\n\n*The first wide release of the song was in Canada in 1982 by [[The Irish Rovers]], released on the album, ''It Was a Night Like This''. Their signature version, produced by  [[Jack Richardson (record producer)|Jack Richardson]], rose to #20 on the RPM charts within a week of its release.<ref>{{cite news|last=RPM Album Charts|title=Adult Contemporary - Volume 37, No. 19, December 25, 1982|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.6164&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=1mqpiqom9hnjn6eoqg7oj1jd34|newspaper=Archives Canada|date=Dec 1982}}</ref>  The single became a seasonal hit, first on country stations, then on Top 40 stations, and today remains a 'seasonal holiday anthem'.<ref>{{cite news|last=Anningston|first=Brett|title= After four decades, group still loves to entertain|newspaper=Times & Transcript|date= Feb 25, 2010}}</ref> The song was also released on the Rovers' 1999 album ''Songs of Christmas''.\n*When the [[San Francisco 49ers]] earned a trip to [[Super Bowl XXIX]], Dr. Elmo released a parody, \"Chargers Got Run Over by the Niners\", predicting the 49ers' victory over their Super Bowl opponents, the [[L.A. Chargers|San Diego Chargers]] (the 49ers ended up winning the game 49-26). Most of the lyrics were actually spent making fun of the 49ers' main NFC rival, the [[Dallas Cowboys]].\n*It has also been covered by [[Family Force 5]] (in the song, the word \"beer\" was edited out and replaced with root beer), and in 1996 by [[Ann Danielewski|Poe]].\n*It was also covered by [[Less Than Jake]] on their album ''[[Goodbye Blue and White]]''.\n*A rock cover version is on the album ''[[We Wish You a Metal Xmas and a Headbanging New Year]]''.\n*Country a cappella band [[Home Free (group)|Home Free]] covered it on their 2014 Christmas album ''Full of Cheer''.\n*[[Reel Big Fish]] covered the song on their 2014 EP ''[[Happy Skalidays]]''.\n*[[Ray Stevens]] covered \"Grandma\" on Clyde Records in 2016.\n*Composer Brooks also has a version on the 2014 self-released ''Randy Brooks' Greatest Hit''.\n*Danish comedy band [[Linie 3]] released a Danish-language cover version of the song in 1984, with a slight change to the original lyrics.\n\n==Parodies==\nIn 1991 a [[Baltimore]] radio station targeted then [[Maryland Governor|Governor of Maryland]] [[William Shaefer]] with a parody entitled \"Shaefer Got Run Over by a Reindeer\".  Shaefer responded by posing for a marketing photo to help boost sales of the tape, the proceeds of which went to charity.<ref>https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1991-12-12-1991346015-story.html</ref>\n\nZ100 Portland Morning Zoo made a [[New Kids on the Block]]-bashing parody of the song for Christmas 1989, entitled \"New Kids Got Run Over by a Reindeer\".\n\nA parody \"Grandpa Got Run Over by a Beer Truck\" was released by [[Da Yoopers]] in 1993. Radio personality [[Bob Rivers]] recorded his own topical parody titled \"[[Osama bin Laden|Osama]] Got Run Over by a Reindeer\" on the 2002 ''[[White Trash Christmas]]'' album.\n\n[[Cledus T. Judd]] in 1996 released a parody called \"Grandpa Got Run Over by a [[John Deere]]\" as a sequel to \"Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer\" and as well did a cover of the song in 2002.\n\n[[Stan Boreson]] sings a Norwegian-American version, \"Lena Got Run Over by a Reindeer\" on his Christmas album, ''Stan Boreson Fractures Christmas''.\n\n[[2 Live Jews]] released a parody titled \"Moisha Got Run Over by a Wheelchair\" on their 1998 album ''Christmas Jews''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/2-Live-Jews-Christmas-Jews/release/5928164|title=2 Live Jews - Christmas Jews|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2018-11-05}}</ref>\n\nOthers include \"Grandma Got Molested at the Airport\" by [[Donny Aldridge]], also sung by Dick Mango; and \"Grandma Got Dismembered by a Chainsaw\".\n\n==Popularity==\nEdison Media Research and Pinnacle Media Worldwide independently survey radio listeners on which Christmas songs they like and dislike.  In both surveys, results of which were reported in 2007, the only song that reached the top of both liked and disliked lists was \"Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer.\"<ref name=\"WashPost\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/12/13/AR2007121302192_pf.html|title=All I Want for Christmas Is Not To Hear That Song|first=Paul|last=Farhi|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=December 14, 2007}}</ref>  Its \"loved\" ratings in the Edison and Pinnacle polls were relatively high\u201447 and 32 percent, respectively\u2014but so were the \"hate\" or \"dislike\" ratings\u201417 and 22 percent.\n\nA major [[Washington, D.C.]] [[radio station]], WASH (97.1 FM), dropped the song from its [[playlist]]. \"It was too polarizing,\" says Bill Hess, [[program director]]. \"It wasn't strong, except with a few people, and it had a lot of negatives.\"<ref name=\"WashPost\"/> The song also gained notoriety at [[Davenport, Iowa]] radio station [[WLLR-FM|WLLR]] in 1985 when a disc jockey played the song 27 times back-to-back during the morning show before station management was able to stop him. The disc jockey, who was suspended, was reportedly depressed and upset that a co-worker had left employment at the station to work out-of-state.<ref>{{cite news |agency=[[United Press International]] |title=Dj's Record Effort Pulls Him Off Air |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=December 19, 1985 |access-date=December 23, 2017 |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1985-12-19/news/8503280214_1_jack-daniels-station-listeners}}</ref>\n\nShropshire claims it is \"a beloved holiday favorite.\" The video of the song was \"a holiday staple on [[MTV]] for many seasons.\" It has been \"incorporated into talking toys and a musical greeting card.\" \"My royalties are four or five times what they were\" 20 years ago, claims Elmo, who performs the song with his [[Bluegrass music|bluegrass]] group year-round.  \"A lot of younger people say it's not really Christmas until they hear it.\"<ref name=\"WashPost\"/>\n\n==Television==\nThe 2000 animated television program ''[[Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer (film)|Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer]]'' portrays the events depicted in the song, though made for children; the cartoon is toned down a bit, so that Grandma survives. Moreover, Santa is actually innocent of the crime, which was instead masterminded by scheming relative Cousin Mel, who is mentioned briefly in the song but made into a gold-digging villainness in the special. Elmo Shropshire narrates the special and voices Grandpa. The special is a staple of [[Cartoon Network]]'s holiday programming and airs every holiday season on [[The CW]] (The special originally aired on the [[WB Network]] every holiday season until the 2006 merger with [[UPN]] to form The CW, where it continues to air today).\n\nIn the 2015 episode of the television show ''[[Scorpion_(TV_series)|Scorpion]]'', titled \"Dam Breakthrough\", three of the main characters sing part of this song, while inhaling helium.\n\nDuring [[Peter Griffin|Peter]]'s imagined funeral in ''[[JOLO (Family Guy)|#JOLO]]'' (episode 14, of [[Family Guy (season 13)|season 13]], of [[Family Guy]]), three small monkeys [[lip sync]] ''Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer''.\n\nIn the second season of the [[NBC]] comedy series ''[[The Good Place]]'', the song is played on repeat (along with \"[[She Hates Me]]\" by [[Puddle of Mudd]]) at a party in the Bad Place attended by demons.\n\n==Music video==\nThe promotional music video for Elmo & Patsy's \"Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer\" was released in the mid-1980s, and aired on [[MTV]] for at least 18 years. The video could also be seen on [[VH1]], [[Country Music Television|CMT]], [[The Nashville Network|TNN]], [[Great American Country|GAC]], and [[VH1 Classic]] during the holiday season, as well as on [[Spike (TV channel)|Spike]]'s official website and [[YouTube]]. Elmo Shropshire played Grandpa and Grandma while Patsy played Cousin Mel.\n\nWhile the family matriarch was run over by Santa Claus's reindeer, she has survived the accident (unlike in the actual song) and thus reappears toward the end of the video, alive and very much well, but somewhat fazed by the trampling. While being escorted inside the house by two policemen, she finally speaks the cautionary last line of the last verse as though commenting on Santa's driving: \"They should NEVER give a license/To a man who drives a sleigh and plays with elves\".\n\n==Chart performance==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!align=\"left\"| Chart (1984)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n| US [[Hot Country Songs|Hot Country Singles]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref name=\"whitburn1\">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944\u20132008|publisher=Record Research, Inc|year=2008|isbn=978-0-89820-177-2|authorlink=Joel Whitburn}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| 92\n|-\n! align=\"left\"|Chart (1992)\n! align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n| US [[Bubbling Under Hot 100 Singles]] (''Billboard'')<ref name=\"whitburn2\">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Top Pop Singles 1955\u20132010|publisher=Record Research, Inc|year=2011|isbn=978-0-89820-188-8|authorlink=Joel Whitburn}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| 12\n|-\n! align=\"left\"|Chart (1997\u20131998)\n! align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n| US Hot Country Singles & Tracks (''Billboard'')<ref name=\"whitburn1\"/>\n| align=\"center\"| 64\n|-\n| US ''Billboard'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]<ref name=\"whitburn2\"/>\n| align=\"center\"| 87\n|-\n! align=\"left\"|Chart (1999\u20132000)\n! align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n| US Hot Country Singles & Tracks (''Billboard'')<ref name=\"whitburn1\"/>\n| align=\"center\"| 48\n|}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Lisi |work=[[The Daily Gazette]] |title=The novelty never wears off for some clever songs written for the season |page=G01 |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SDGB&p_theme=sdgb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=1110FC8626A399A9&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |date=December 10, 2000 |accessdate=February 26, 2010}}\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*\n*[http://www.billboard.com/articles/chartbeat/1481537/weekly-chart-notes-dr-elmos-grandma-gets-her-revenge 2012 Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer #1 on the billboard charts - 1st time in 27 years.]\n*{{YouTube|OHz0T3aSLFU|2009/2010 Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer promotion on TV and radio}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081206013150/http://www.theballadeers.com/IR_D23_night_like_this.htm 2001 The Balladeers, It Was A Night Like This]\n*[http://www.drelmo.com/albums.html Dr. Elmo/Grandma Official WebSite]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101204045834/http://www.aolnews.com/weird-news/article/grannies-learn-to-love-grandma-got-run-over-by-a-reindeer/19726026 Grannies Learn to Love 'Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer' Monica Garske AOL NEWS]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101204072554/http://www.radio-info.com/programming/country/grandma-singer-dr-elmo-is-having-the-last-laugh 2010 article by Phyllis Stark]\n*[http://www.songfacts.com/detail.php?id=2408 Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer Songfacts]\n*[http://www.pressdemocrat.com/article/20121204/ARTICLES/121209833?p=2&tc=pg 2012 Novelty reindeer song still has legs]\n*[http://frontporchexpressions.com/2013/12/19/singers-persistence-turns-reindeer-song-into-bestseller/ 2013 Singer\u2019s persistence turns reindeer song into bestseller ]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20131224115919/http://www.csnbayarea.com/show/391546/episode/657736 2013 Dr. Elmo on Comcast/Yahoo Sports Network]\n*{{YouTube|TfSb6J4jhcU|A Remix of the original song \"Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer.\" Produced and performed by Dr. Elmo, Written by Randy Brooks, re-mixed by Frank Martin.}}\n*{{YouTube|Zlywn0D1eIw|2016 Interview with Randy Brooks and his famous song}}\n\n[[Category:Black comedy music]]\n[[Category:Comedy songs]]\n[[Category:Christmas novelty songs]]\n[[Category:American Christmas songs]]\n[[Category:1979 songs]]\n[[Category:Epic Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs about old age]]\n[[Category:Songs about death]]\n[[Category:Songs about animals]]\n[[Category:Novelty songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||the film|Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer (film)|the ''Grey's Anatomy'' episode|Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer (Grey's Anatomy)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer\n| cover      = Single Elmo & Patsy-Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| caption    = Picture sleeve of 1984 release by [[Epic Records]] <small>(34-04703)</small>\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Elmo Shropshire|Elmo & Patsy]]\n| album      = Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer\n| B-side     = {{ubl|\"Christmas\" <small>(Elmo 'n' Patsy; Oink; Soundwaves)</small>|\"Percy, The Puny Poinsettia\" <small>([[Epic Records|Epic]])</small>}}\n| released   = 1979 <small>(Elmo 'n' Patsy)</small><br/>1982 <small>(Oink; Soundwaves)</small><br/>1984 <small>([[Epic Records|Epic]])</small>\n| format     = [[Single (music)|7-inch]]\n| recorded   = 1978\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Christmas music|Christmas]], [[country music|country]], [[Novelty song|novelty]], [[pop music|pop]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=30}} <small>(Elmo 'n' Patsy; Oink; Soundwaves)</small><br/>{{Duration|m=3|s=26}} <small>([[Epic Records|Epic]])</small>\n| label      = Elmo 'n' Patsy <small>2984</small><br/>Oink <small>2984</small><br />Soundwaves <small>4658</small><br />[[Epic Records|Epic]] <small>34-04703</small>\n| writer     = Randy Brooks\n| producer   = Gary Potterton\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\"'''Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer'''\" is a [[novelty song|novelty]] [[Christmas music|Christmas song]]. Written by Randy Brooks, the song was originally performed by the husband-and-wife duo of [[Elmo Shropshire|Elmo]] and Patsy Trigg Shropshire in 1979.\n\n==Synopsis==\nIn the lyrics, a [[Grandparent|grandmother]] is celebrating at a Christmas Eve party with her family when, while off her medication and [[alcohol intoxication|drunk]] on spiked [[eggnog]], she staggers outside into a [[Winter storm|snowstorm]] against the pleas of everyone in the room. She is found the next day, trampled; [[Santa Claus]] and his [[reindeer]] are determined to be the culprits when \"incriminating Claus marks\" are found on Grandma's back. The second and third verses describe the Christmas gathering where \"all the family's dressed in black\" to [[mourn]] her death and wonders if all the Christmas gifts they bought for her should be returned (the consensus is a firm yes). Christmas dinner otherwise goes on as normal, with a centerpiece of [[roast goose]], [[figgy pudding]] for dessert, and \"blue and silver candles\" to match Grandma's hairpiece; the newly widowed Grandpa seems completely unfazed by his wife's demise and spends the holiday \"[[Blue\u2013Gray Football Classic|watching football]], drinking beer and playing cards with Cousin Mel\" (who, while not stated as such in the lyrics, is an attractive and much younger woman in the music video and animated film). The [[Result|upshot]] is a warning to the listeners to beware, because \"a man who drives a sleigh and plays with elves\" should never receive a driver's license.\n\nIn the music video, in which Elmo plays both Grandma and Grandpa while Patsy plays Cousin Mel, Grandma survives the attack and makes a triumphant return through the chimney.\n\n==Releases==\nAccording to Brooks, he played the song while sitting in with Elmo and Patsy at the Hyatt [[Lake Tahoe]] in December 1978, and after the show they had him make a cassette of the song for them to learn. A year later, they were selling 45s of the song from the stage, with Elmo himself appearing in drag on the album cover as \"Grandma\".\n\nThe song was originally self-released in [[San Francisco]] by the Shropshires in 1979 on their own record label (on \"Elmo 'n' Patsy\" #2984), with the B-side titled \"Christmas\". Initial copies appeared on a cream-colored label, with a sketch of a pig clearly visible, at left. Once initial copies had sold out, later-pressed #2984 cream-colored 45 label copies retained the same pig sketch, but decided to both move the sketch, and add the word \"Oink\", to the top of the 45's label. Meanwhile, the duo's names were moved to the bottom of the label, below the song title. By the early 1980s, the song was becoming a seasonal hit, first on [[country music|country stations]] and then on [[Contemporary Hit Radio|Top 40 stations]]. Oink Records, still based in [[Windsor, California]], continued distribution of the 45 rpm record in the western U.S., with \"Nationwide Sound Distributors\" (NSD) of [[Nashville, Tennessee]], pressing and distributing the song on its [[Soundwaves Records]] in the eastern U.S., peaking at #92 on the country singles charts. In 1982, the duo both re-recorded and re-released the song as a single, again as Oink #2984. But this time, Oink chose to handle all nationwide product distribution themselves, ending the old NSD-Soundwaves agreement. Re-recorded Oink #2984 45 copies appeared on a white label, not a cream-colored label, however. That is the easiest way (aside from listening to the 45 itself) to differentiate between the original 1979 Oink #2984 recording and its now-much-more familiar, 1982 re-recording. An entire LP, named after their hit song, was also recorded in 1982, and was initially released as Oink #8223. In 1984, with the song now a big hit nationally, [[Sony Music Entertainment|CBS Records]] was interested in re-issuing both the 1982 Oink 45 re-recording, and the 1982 Oink LP. Soon after, [[Epic Records]] acquired the rights to both, from Elmo and Patsy. The Epic #04703 45 opted to replace the Oink 45's B-side, \"Christmas\", with a track from the LP, (\"Percy, the Puny [[Poinsettia]]\"). Epic's 1984 re-release of the 1982 Oink LP was a straight re-issue, on Epic #39931. By the end of 1984, it was reported that sales of \"Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer\" were, by record label: Oink: 50,000 45s sold; Soundwaves: 175,000 45s sold; Epic: 150,000 45s sold and 90,000 LPs sold. The Epic Records version charted at #64 on the country charts in 1998 and #48 in 1999.\n\nThe original version was released in the [[United Kingdom]] on [[Stiff Records]] (BUY 99) in 1980. It did not chart.\n\nOther releases by the original artist(s) would follow:\n\n*Following the Shropshires' divorce, Elmo re-recorded it solo in 1992 and again in 2000.\n*[[SonyBMG]] released ''Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer'' by [[Dr. Elmo]] in 2002. The 2002 re-recording is distinguished by a slightly different opening note in the chorus melody.\n*[[Madacy]] Records released a ''Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer'' gift tin (CD/DVD/Xmas stocking) by [[Dr. Elmo]] in 2007.\n*[[Time Life]] Records released ''Dr. Elmo's Bluegrass Christmas'' in 2010, which featured a bluegrass instrumental of \"Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer.\"\n\nA sequel, titled \"Grandpa's Gonna Sue the Pants Off of Santa\", in which Grandpa gets lawyers to fight Santa in court, was released by [[Elmo Shropshire]] on his album ''Dr. Elmo's Twisted Christmas'' (1992).\n\n==Covers==\nThe song has been recorded by other acts.\n\n*The first wide release of the song was in Canada in 1982 by [[The Irish Rovers]], released on the album, ''It Was a Night Like This''. Their signature version, produced by  [[Jack Richardson (record producer)|Jack Richardson]], rose to #20 on the RPM charts within a week of its release.<ref>{{cite news|last=RPM Album Charts|title=Adult Contemporary - Volume 37, No. 19, December 25, 1982|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.6164&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=1mqpiqom9hnjn6eoqg7oj1jd34|newspaper=Archives Canada|date=Dec 1982}}</ref>  The single became a seasonal hit, first on country stations, then on Top 40 stations, and today remains a 'seasonal holiday anthem'.<ref>{{cite news|last=Anningston|first=Brett|title= After four decades, group still loves to entertain|newspaper=Times & Transcript|date= Feb 25, 2010}}</ref> The song was also released on the Rovers' 1999 album ''Songs of Christmas''.\n*When the [[San Francisco 49ers]] earned a trip to [[Super Bowl XXIX]], Dr. Elmo released a parody, \"Chargers Got Run Over by the Niners\", predicting the 49ers' victory over their Super Bowl opponents, the [[L.A. Chargers|San Diego Chargers]] (the 49ers ended up winning the game 49-26). Most of the lyrics were actually spent making fun of the 49ers' main NFC rival, the [[Dallas Cowboys]].\n*It has also been covered by [[Family Force 5]] (in the song, the word \"beer\" was edited out and replaced with root beer), and in 1996 by [[Ann Danielewski|Poe]].\n*It was also covered by [[Less Than Jake]] on their album ''[[Goodbye Blue and White]]''.\n*A rock cover version is on the album ''[[We Wish You a Metal Xmas and a Headbanging New Year]]''.\n*Country a cappella band [[Home Free (group)|Home Free]] covered it on their 2014 Christmas album ''Full of Cheer''.\n*[[Reel Big Fish]] covered the song on their 2014 EP ''[[Happy Skalidays]]''.\n*[[Ray Stevens]] covered \"Grandma\" on Clyde Records in 2016.\n*Composer Brooks also has a version on the 2014 self-released ''Randy Brooks' Greatest Hit''.\n*Danish comedy band [[Linie 3]] released a Danish-language cover version of the song in 1984, with a slight change to the original lyrics.\n\n==Parodies==\nIn 1991 a [[Baltimore]] radio station targeted then [[Maryland Governor|Governor of Maryland]] [[William Shaefer]] with a parody entitled \"Shaefer Got Run Over by a Reindeer\".  Shaefer responded by posing for a marketing photo to help boost sales of the tape, the proceeds of which went to charity.<ref>https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1991-12-12-1991346015-story.html</ref>\n\nZ100 Portland Morning Zoo made a [[New Kids on the Block]]-bashing parody of the song for Christmas 1989, entitled \"New Kids Got Run Over by a Reindeer\".\n\nA parody \"Grandpa Got Run Over by a Beer Truck\" was released by [[Da Yoopers]] in 1993. Radio personality [[Bob Rivers]] recorded his own topical parody titled \"[[Osama bin Laden|Osama]] Got Run Over by a Reindeer\" on the 2002 ''[[White Trash Christmas]]'' album.\n\n[[Cledus T. Judd]] in 1996 released a parody called \"Grandpa Got Run Over by a [[John Deere]]\" as a sequel to \"Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer\" and as well did a cover of the song in 2002.\n\n[[Stan Boreson]] sings a Norwegian-American version, \"Lena Got Run Over by a Reindeer\" on his Christmas album, ''Stan Boreson Fractures Christmas''.\n\n[[2 Live Jews]] released a parody titled \"Moisha Got Run Over by a Wheelchair\" on their 1998 album ''Christmas Jews''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/2-Live-Jews-Christmas-Jews/release/5928164|title=2 Live Jews - Christmas Jews|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2018-11-05}}</ref>\n\nOthers include \"Grandma Got Molested at the Airport\" by [[Donny Aldridge]], also sung by Dick Mango; and \"Grandma Got Dismembered by a Chainsaw\".\n\n==Popularity==\nEdison Media Research and Pinnacle Media Worldwide independently survey radio listeners on which Christmas songs they like and dislike.  In both surveys, results of which were reported in 2007, the only song that reached the top of both liked and disliked lists was \"Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer.\"<ref name=\"WashPost\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/12/13/AR2007121302192_pf.html|title=All I Want for Christmas Is Not To Hear That Song|first=Paul|last=Farhi|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=December 14, 2007}}</ref>  Its \"loved\" ratings in the Edison and Pinnacle polls were relatively high\u201447 and 32 percent, respectively\u2014but so were the \"hate\" or \"dislike\" ratings\u201417 and 22 percent.\n\nA major [[Washington, D.C.]] [[radio station]], WASH (97.1 FM), dropped the song from its [[playlist]]. \"It was too polarizing,\" says Bill Hess, [[program director]]. \"It wasn't strong, except with a few people, and it had a lot of negatives.\"<ref name=\"WashPost\"/> The song also gained notoriety at [[Davenport, Iowa]] radio station [[WLLR-FM|WLLR]] in 1985 when a disc jockey played the song 27 times back-to-back during the morning show before station management was able to stop him. The disc jockey, who was suspended, was reportedly depressed and upset that a co-worker had left employment at the station to work out-of-state.<ref>{{cite news |agency=[[United Press International]] |title=Dj's Record Effort Pulls Him Off Air |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=December 19, 1985 |access-date=December 23, 2017 |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1985-12-19/news/8503280214_1_jack-daniels-station-listeners}}</ref>\n\nShropshire claims it is \"a beloved holiday favorite.\" The video of the song was \"a holiday staple on [[MTV]] for many seasons.\" It has been \"incorporated into talking toys and a musical greeting card.\" \"My royalties are four or five times what they were\" 20 years ago, claims Elmo, who performs the song with his [[Bluegrass music|bluegrass]] group year-round.  \"A lot of younger people say it's not really Christmas until they hear it.\"<ref name=\"WashPost\"/>\n\n==Television==\nThe 2000 animated television program ''[[Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer (film)|Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer]]'' portrays the events depicted in the song, though made for children; the cartoon is toned down a bit, so that Grandma survives. Moreover, Santa is actually innocent of the crime, which was instead masterminded by scheming relative Cousin Mel, who is mentioned briefly in the song but made into a gold-digging villainness in the special. Elmo Shropshire narrates the special and voices Grandpa. The special is a staple of [[Cartoon Network]]'s holiday programming and airs every holiday season on [[The CW]] (The special originally aired on the [[WB Network]] every holiday season until the 2006 merger with [[UPN]] to form The CW, where it continues to air today).\n\nIn the 2015 episode of the television show ''[[Scorpion_(TV_series)|Scorpion]]'', titled \"Dam Breakthrough\", three of the main characters sing part of this song, while inhaling helium.\n\nDuring [[Peter Griffin|Peter]]'s imagined funeral in ''[[JOLO (Family Guy)|#JOLO]]'' (episode 14, of [[Family Guy (season 13)|season 13]], of [[Family Guy]]), three small monkeys [[lip sync]] ''Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer''.\n\nIn the second season of the [[NBC]] comedy series ''[[The Good Place]]'', the song is played on repeat (along with \"[[She Hates Me]]\" by [[Puddle of Mudd]]) at a party in the Bad Place attended by demons.\n\n==Music video==\nThe promotional music video for Elmo & Patsy's \"Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer\" was released in the mid-1980s, and aired on [[MTV]] for at least 18 years. The video could also be seen on [[VH1]], [[Country Music Television|CMT]], [[The Nashville Network|TNN]], [[Great American Country|GAC]], and [[VH1 Classic]] during the holiday season, as well as on [[Spike (TV channel)|Spike]]'s official website and [[YouTube]]. Elmo Shropshire played Grandpa and Grandma while Patsy played Cousin Mel.\n\nWhile the family matriarch was run over by Santa Claus's reindeer, she has survived the accident (unlike in the actual song) and thus reappears toward the end of the video, alive and very much well, but somewhat fazed by the trampling. While being escorted inside the house by two policemen, she finally speaks the cautionary last line of the last verse as though commenting on Santa's driving: \"They should NEVER give a license/To a man who drives a sleigh and plays with elves\".\n\n==Chart performance==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!align=\"left\"| Chart (1984)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n| US [[Hot Country Songs|Hot Country Singles]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref name=\"whitburn1\">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944\u20132008|publisher=Record Research, Inc|year=2008|isbn=978-0-89820-177-2|authorlink=Joel Whitburn}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| 92\n|-\n! align=\"left\"|Chart (1992)\n! align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n| US [[Bubbling Under Hot 100 Singles]] (''Billboard'')<ref name=\"whitburn2\">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Top Pop Singles 1955\u20132010|publisher=Record Research, Inc|year=2011|isbn=978-0-89820-188-8|authorlink=Joel Whitburn}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| 12\n|-\n! align=\"left\"|Chart (1997\u20131998)\n